<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Four Arrested For People Smuggling  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- A Chinese court sentenced to prison four
''snakeheads,'' or people-smugglers, for sneaking 13 people out of
the country, state-run media reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Ringleader Yu Guangyou was given seven years on Aug. 8 by a
court in the city of Lianyungang, Jiangsu province, while his
cohorts received sentences of up to five years, Xinhua News agency
said.
</P>
<P>
   Enlisting the help of sailors Wang Qi, Zhang Linjing and Ni
Aizhong, Yu hid the migrants aboard ships and smuggled them out of
China in small groups over the course of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The report said Yu took payment from the migrants for helping
them leave the country. It did not give the stowaways'
destinations.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate case, seven people, including three Taiwanese,
were arrested in China's Fujian province for conspiring to smuggle
women to Taiwan to work as prostitutes, Xinhua said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese media have carried numerous reports of police action
against snakeheads and migrants after 58 illegal Chinese immigrants
were found dead in a truck at the English port town of Dover in
June.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
