<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taiwan President Cancels U.S. Event  </HEADLINE>
By WILLIAM FOREMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- Taiwanese officials showed no signs of
disappointment or anger Sunday about the cancellation of a rare
U.S. meeting between their president and members of Congress -- a
gathering that would have infuriated rival China.
</P>
<P>
   Hours before President Chen Shui-bian was to board a plane for
the United States, a Foreign Ministry official downplayed the
canceled meeting, telling reporters that Chen's 16-hour layover in
Los Angeles was too brief for special meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ''President Chen will spend most of his time in the hotel,''
said Wu Tzu-dan, a vice foreign minister. ''There's no time to do
anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting permission to stop in the United States before he
travels to the Caribbean, Central America and Africa was a big
enough victory for Chen. It was unlikely that the Taiwanese leader,
who took office May 20, would do anything that strains Taiwan's
relationship with America, the island's most important friend.
</P>
<P>
   By giving Chen a transit visa, Washington risked angering China,
which insists that Taiwan is a breakaway province that should
reunify with the mainland. Beijing opposes any activities -- such as
official U.S. visits -- that give the island increased international
legitimacy. Only 29 nations, mostly small developing countries,
have diplomatic ties with Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   China began protesting shortly after Chen announced that he was
given a U.S. transit visa, warning that his visit could severely
damage U.S. ties with China. The U.S. State Department pressured
Chen not to meet with lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Chen was invited to gather with members of Congress at a private
home Sunday in Los Angeles. Four California representatives were to
attend the meeting: Democrats Nancy Pelosi and Howard Berman and
Republicans Christopher Cox and Dana Rohrabacher.
</P>
<P>
   But the gathering's organizer, Rep. Sam Gejdenson, a Connecticut
Democrat, said Chen informed him Saturday night that he was pulling
out of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday in Taipei, the issue was the hot topic at a
pre-departure news conference at the Presidential Office. Reporters
pressed Wu, the vice foreign minister, about whether there was
still a chance Chen would meet with the lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ''As far as I know, there is no such arrangement,'' Wu said.
</P>
<P>
   The official said that Chen planned to go directly to his hotel
after he lands Sunday evening. He will meet with Chen Chien-jen,
Taiwan's de facto ambassador to the United States, who has
organized a banquet for Chen and his delegation in the president's
hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Early the next morning, the group will have to depart for the
airport, following a tight schedule that leaves little time for
anything else, Wu said.
</P>
<P>
   Wu emphasized that the stop in Los Angeles was strictly a
transit visit and stretching it into an official visit would be
offending U.S. goodwill.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't feel like there's any reason to do that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Chen's itinerary includes the Dominican Republic (Aug. 14-17),
Nicaragua (Aug. 17-18), Costa Rica (Aug 18-19), Gambia (Aug.
20-21), Burkina Faso (Aug. 21-23), Chad (Aug. 23-25) and a Dubai
stopover (Aug. 25-26).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-13-00 0138 </TRAILER>
