<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 02:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Koreas Reunions Make Progress  </HEADLINE>
By KYONG-HWA SEOK
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- In sharp contrast with South Korea,
the rival North will send many state-decorated luminaries for
family reunions in Seoul this week -- a sign of politics intruding
on the supposedly humanitarian project.
</P>
<P>
   As part of a deal struck at a historic summit of their leaders
in June, the Koreas will exchange 100 people each Tuesday for four
days of temporary reunions with relatives they have not seen for a
half century.
</P>
<P>
   The reunions, the first since 1985, are a symbol of the thaw
following the first-ever summit between the two Koreas, which have
been divided since 1945. The encounter between the South's
President Kim Dae-jung and the North's Kim Jong Il provided the
best chance yet for peace on the Korean peninsula, the Cold War's
last holdout.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the Koreas have stopped propaganda broadcasts to each
other and agreed to reopen border liaison offices Monday and
connect a cross-border railway that was cut off just before the
Korean War broke out in 1950.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea's leader was quoted this weekend as saying he
believes that inter-Korea relations have improved significantly
since the historic summit.
</P>
<P>
   ''The overall relations between the North and the South have
developed in favor of national reconciliation, unity and
reunification,'' Kim Jong Il was quoted as saying in a report by
the country's foreign news outlet, KCNA.
</P>
<P>
   Out of more than 75,000 people who had applied for this week's
reunions with their relatives in the North, South Korea chose its
100 finalists through a computer lottery. Most of them are over 70
years old and include no notables.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the North Korean list includes a renowned poet,
painter, film maker, scientist and many other celebrated people.
All the Northern visitors are South Korean natives who defected to
the North.
</P>
<P>
   About 1.2 million North Koreans fled to South Korea during the
three-year Korean War. Thousands of South Koreans are believed to
have gone to the North voluntarily or after being inducted into the
North's army.
</P>
<P>
   ''The composition of the North's delegation carries a political
message that South Korean defectors are well-treated and well-off
in the North,'' said Nam Ju-hong, a professor at Seoul's Kyonggi
University.
</P>
<P>
   Seoul government officials said they were confused about the
criteria North Korea might have used in selecting its visitors,
because some who have direct kin in South Korea were dropped, while
others will be coming to see their in-laws.
</P>
<P>
   ''Loyalty to its system appears to have been the North's most
important criteria,'' said Song Young-dae, a former Cabinet member
who got involved in negotiations with North Korea in the early
1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Seoul officials said that except in some exceptional cases,
North Korean families who have defectors in South Korea generally
live as social outcasts and are put on the government blacklist.
</P>
<P>
   The most notable member of the North Korean delegation is Yoo Mi
Young, 78, the wife of former South Korean Foreign Minister Choi
Duk Shin who defected to the North in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Choi, a retired army general, served as foreign minister under
the military junta led by dictator Park Chung-hee in 1961. He later
became Seoul's ambassador to West Germany before the German
unification and headed the indigenous Korean religion, Chondo.
</P>
<P>
   Choi, with his wife, fled South Korea in 1976 after police
launched an investigation into allegations that he embezzled
official funds of the religion. He died in North Korea in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Choi was treated as a national hero in North Korea. He headed a
political party based on the Chondo religion. After he died, his
wife took over the party.
</P>
<P>
   Many South Koreans are upset by the North's choice of Yoo as
head of its delegation for the family reunions.
</P>
<P>
   The North's decision to send ''such an individual to the South
... is nothing short of contempt,'' said Seoul's leading
conservative newspaper Chosun in an editorial.
</P>
<P>
   Yoo's two children in Seoul reportedly are reluctant to meet
their mother. They did not apply for a reunion with her.
</P>
<P>
   Her 48-year-old youngest daughter in Seoul, Choi Soon-hae,
reportedly said through a friend that if her mother wants to meet
her, she will agree to see her. But her second son in Seoul, Choi
In-koo, 53, said through his wife that he does not want to see her.
</P>
<P>
   South Koreans generally despise the families of defectors to
North Korea. Depite a thaw brought on by the June summit, suspicion
runs deep among South Koreans toward the North.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-13-00 0201 </TRAILER>
