<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kidnap Suspect Arrested in Calif.  </HEADLINE>
By RON HARRIS
<TEXT>
<P>
   VALLEJO, Calif. (AP) -- An 8-year-old girl missing for three days
made a daring escape from her abductor Saturday, dashing from his
car to the safety of a passing truck, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Midsi Sanchez, who disappeared on the way home from school
Thursday, had her leg restrained in her captor's vehicle, but was
able to free herself, bolt from the car and flag down the passing
driver in Santa Clara, said Anton Morec, a spokesman for the Santa
Clara Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   ''He pulled up, she jumped up immediately into his vehicle. She
told the driver she had been kidnapped and she needed help,'' Morec
said. ''She did all the right things. Her instincts were very good
for an 8-year-old.''
</P>
<P>
   The suspect chased her as she ran down the street, but fled when
he saw she had reached the driver, said Lt. JoAnn West of the
Vallejo Police Department. West said the driver recognized the
suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Police arrested Curtis Dean Anderson, KCBS reported. Anderson,
39, had a previous conviction for kidnapping and served time in the
Solano County jail for that conviction, West said. He has also has
had previous arrests for weapons violations, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Police believe Anderson drove Midsi to an industrial area of
Santa Clara and parked the car near a business where he had worked
and went in. Police said Midsi's leg was shackled and they believe
when Anderson left, she took a key from the front, unlocked the
shackles and escaped.
</P>
<P>
   Police believe he and Midsi spent Friday night in the car near
the business, but are not sure where she spent Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Clara is about 45 miles south of San Francisco and 70
miles southwest of Vallejo, where Midsi lives and was last seen.
</P>
<P>
   Midsi's family awaited her return Saturday night with balloons
and signs welcoming her back. The family had originally planned to
celebrate the girl's Aug. 3 birthday on Saturday, and decided to
combine the birthday and welcoming celebrations.
</P>
<P>
   Midsi was to be examined at an area hospital for injuries and
was to be reunited with her parents late Saturday. She was very
hungry and ate several hamburgers as police questioned her about
her ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   Midsi's parents talked to the girl by phone Saturday, and
expressed relief at her return.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm grateful,'' said her mother Susana Velasco. ''She is a
hero; she got away. She outsmarted him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
