<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kashmir Land Mines Kill Six  </HEADLINE>
By BINOO JOSHI
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAMMU, India (AP) -- Two land mines exploded under buses carrying
paramilitary troops in Kashmir on Sunday, killing six soldiers in
stepped-up violence before India's Independence Day, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Three other explosions also rocked the Himalayan province, the
seat of an Islamic insurgency that has left 25,000 people dead in
the last 11 years. In all, 42 people were reported hurt in addition
to the six killed.
</P>
<P>
   The Pakistan-based Hezb-ul Mujahedeen -- the largest of the
Muslim rebel groups here -- claimed responsibility for the mine
explosions at Kud, a village 50 miles north of Jammu, the winter
capital of Indian-controlled Kashmir. The group said it would
increase attacks against Indian troops in the province.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are committed to end Indian rule in Kashmir and our
activities will escalate,'' Salim Hashmi, a Hezb-ul Mujahedeen
spokesman in the Pakistani capital, Islamabad, told The Associated
Press by telephone.
</P>
<P>
   Five soldiers of the Border Security Force were killed in the
first blast, on the Jammu-Srinagar Highway. Soldiers immediately
halted traffic and looked for land mines along the route.
</P>
<P>
   When traffic resumed two hours later, another land mine went off
about a half-mile away. The second blast damaged a bus and killed
one soldier.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials said both mines apparently were triggered by a
remote control device.
</P>
<P>
   The explosions left 40 soldiers hospitalized at a hospital in
Udhampur. Doctors said 10 soldiers were in critical condition.
</P>
<P>
   The buses were part of a convoy carrying security personnel to
Srinagar, 185 miles to the north, ahead of Tuesday's Independence
Day celebration. Militants fighting Indian security forces in
Kashmir usually increase violence against the government during the
run-up to the Aug. 15 celebration, and separatist guerrilla groups
have vowed to wreck the festivities again this year.
</P>
<P>
   The other three explosions, including a grenade hurled by
militants and another land mine blast, left two people injured.
</P>
<P>
   In Srinagar, police sealed an area around the Bakshi Stadium
where the Independence Day parade is held every year. Militants
usually fire rockets and grenades toward the stadium to disrupt the
celebrations.
</P>
<P>
   Police set up metal barricades on the roads to check all
vehicles in the area. Passengers on buses were frisked with metal
detectors. Many residents stayed indoors.
</P>
<P>
   The mountainous province of Kashmir is divided between India and
Pakistan, both of which claim it in its entirety. The Islamic
guerillas want Indian-controlled Kashmir to break away from heavily
Hindu India and either remain independent or become part of mostly
Muslim Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   Attacks here increased after Kashmir's main guerrilla group, the
Pakistan-based Hezb-ul Mujahedeen, called off a brief cease-fire
this week. The group wanted India to involve Pakistan in talks on
resolving the Kashmir dispute, but India refused.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, militants set off two powerful bombs in downtown
Srinagar, killing 14 soldiers and journalists and wounding 25
others. On Saturday, suspected guerrillas lobbed a grenade near the
Hazratbal Mosque in Srinagar, wounding two Hungarian and two
Kashmiri women.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
