<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 10:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barricaded man shoots three officers during Brooklyn incident  </HEADLINE>
AP Photos
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - A gunman engaged police in a standoff at his
Brooklyn home, shooting and wounding four officers before he was
killed Saturday night, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   The almost seven-hour faceoff with Albert Alalouf began Saturday
afternoon after his parents had gone to the 61st Precinct in
Brooklyn to report that he had purchased several weapons on Friday,
and then told them he intended to ''shoot and kill police
officers,'' Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said.
</P>
<P>
   Officer Gregory John was among the first officers to respond to
Alalouf's residence in the Gravesend section of Brooklyn, where he
opened fire with his shotgun at about 1:30 p.m. The officers
returned fire, forcing Alalouf back inside the home at 16 Parkway
Court, the mayor said.
</P>
<P>
   John, 32, an Emergency Service Unit officer with 10 years on the
job, was hit in the shoulder, police said. He was reported in
stable condition at Kings County Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Alalouf remained barricaded inside the home as police circled
the residence. At about 8 p.m., officers searching the perimeter of
the home approached the front door and came across Alalouf, who
again opened fire, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Officer James McGrath, 33, suffered a graze wound to the face,
and Officer Jose Guerra, 34, was struck in the face and leg, said
Officer Louis Cruz, a police spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect fled out the back window, where an addition officer,
Jose Ocasio, 43, was shot once in the left calf, Cruz said.
</P>
<P>
   Police fired back and Alalouf was fatally wounded. He was
pronounced dead at the scene, said Detective Joseph Pentangelo.
</P>
<P>
   McGrath and Guerra, both members of the Emergency Service Unit,
were taken to Kings County Hospital and treated.
</P>
<P>
   Three other officers were treated for injuries that were not
gunshot-related, including scratches.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities credited John's bulletproof vest with saving his
life.
</P>
<P>
   After the ordeal was over Saturday, Giuliani displayed the
officer's Kevlar vest, which contained at least eight holes where
the buckshot had torn into it.
</P>
<P>
   John actually wore two vests - his personal vest beneath his
uniform, and a heavier ESU vest worn over his clothes.
</P>
<P>
   ''Thank God for the vest,'' Giuliani said.
</P>
</TEXT>
