<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 11:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shipwreck uncovered 175 years after sinking  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WESTPORT, N.Y. (AP) - A group of young shipmen from a small
waterside community perishes when an autumn storm capsizes their
vessel as it travels home.
</P>
<P>
   Sound like this summer's hit movie? It's the tale behind this
summer's historical find on Lake Champlain.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers announced Saturday that they found a ship that sank
almost two centuries ago in Lake Champlain. The canal-schooner that
took five lives with it in 1825 is in nearly perfect condition,
researchers announced at the former family homestead of Jacob
Halstead, the captain of the doomed ship.
</P>
<P>
   Historians said the find is significant since the Troy is the
only example of an early sailing-canal boat.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is the first place in North America where these vessels
appeared,'' said Arthur Cohn of the Lake Champlain Maritime Museum.
''It's one of the most spectacular wrecks I've ever seen,''
</P>
<P>
   ''It must have rocketed to the bottom and hit with an impact
sufficient to bury the bow,'' he added. ''There's been some
deterioration to the stern, but the rest of the hull is in
remarkably good shape.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohn did not give the exact location, saying the site is
sensitive because it may still contain human remains.
</P>
<P>
   ''This shipwreck was a monumental tragedy for the village of
Westport,'' Cohn said. ''Five young men lost their lives. That had
to be a horrific experience for this small community to deal
with.''
</P>
<P>
   Two people on shore saw the struggling boat a few minutes before
it went down Nov. 23, according to newspaper accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Jacob Halstead and his 13-year-old brother, George, the
accident took the lives of Jacob Pardee, the captain's half
brother, and two crewmen, Daniel Cannon and John Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mother and sister were sitting at home in the Halstead house,
listening through the storm for the sound of homecoming footsteps
as the night wore on,'' Caroline Halstead Royce wrote in 1902 in
''A History of Westport.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Suddenly they heard the boys on the doorsteps, stomping off
the snow in the entry as they were wont to do before coming in,''
Royce wrote. ''The women sprang to the door and opened it, stepped
to the outer door and looked down upon the light carpet of
untrodden snow which lay before it and then crept trembling back to
the fireside, knowing that the son and brothers would never sit
with them again within its light.''
</P>
<P>
   A memorial stone remembering the crew sits in Westport Village
Cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   When the Champlain canal opened in 1823, schooners were used to
haul iron ore to the canal, where the cargo was transferred to
canal barges.
</P>
<P>
   By 1825, the sailing-canal boat was developed to eliminate cargo
transport. Sails were used to propel the boats, and a lowered mast
navigated the canal.
</P>
<P>
   Sails made the canal boats, which floated in shallow water,
top-heavy and unstable. Though designed with a center board on
bottom to improve stability, the boards were often too small to
keep many ships upright.
</P>
<P>
   The Maritime Museum found the vessel while conducting a
several-year project to map the lake bottom and catalog shipwrecks
and artifacts.
</P>
<P>
   The Troy is the second major shipwreck discovery the museum has
announced this year. A railroad drawboat from the 1870s was found
near Port Henry.
</P>
<P>
   Westport is 106 miles north of Albany.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
