<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 12:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roads, bridges, dams washed out by downpours  </HEADLINE>
By AMY WESTFELDT
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPARTA, N.J. (AP) - The Musconetcong River in northwest New
Jersey was cresting at some points Sunday - a result of torrential
downpours the day before - prompting officials to evacuate
residents of one town and put others on alert.
</P>
<P>
   State officials estimated that Saturday's heavy rains and
flooding caused several million dollars worth of damage in northern
New Jersey, washing out bridges and roads and bursting dams.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christie Whitman flew over the mud-soaked counties Sunday
morning to view the damage.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Rivoli, director of the Warren County Office of
Emergency Management, said water was breaching the Musconetcong
River, which flows out of Sussex County and borders Morris and
Warren counties, and were worried that it could overflow at any
time.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of Hackettstown were being evacuated and other towns
were on alert.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've notified all municipalities along the river and they're
telling residents that there's a possibility that the river could
flood. At this point we're watching the water level to see how it
makes its way down stream,'' Rivoli said. ''Everybody's got what we
call a 'heads up.'''
</P>
<P>
   The National Weather Service issued a flash flood warning Sunday
morning for parts of Morris, Warren, Hunterdon and Sussex counties
due to river flooding.
</P>
<P>
   In Stanhope, officials were worried that a dam on Furnace Pond
could burst due to the water pressure, Rivoli said.
</P>
<P>
   The water pressure already had eroded a drainage pipe, enlarging
it from about 3-feet in diameter to 8, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a pond that about seven municipalities empty their
stormwater into,'' he said. ''State Police and dam safety people
said it's holding, but could go at any time.''
</P>
<P>
   In Sparta, one of the hardest-hit areas, three roads and three
bridges were destroyed by the torrential downpours, which dumped 14
inches of rain on the township, said Police Sgt. Russell Smith.
</P>
<P>
   The force of all that water also burst the dam on Seneca Lake, a
small, private lake surrounded by homes in Sussex County, the
northernmost part of the state.
</P>
<P>
   No injuries were reported, and officials said no hazardous
materials had been released, he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, police tape surrounded the small beach at the empty
lake, which smelled of dead fish.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Brunetti, 43, said the lake emptied of its thousands of
gallons of water in one hour Saturday evening. It was ''just a big
hole, and the dock floating away,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said the township was receiving help from Sussex County
officials, State Police and the American Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everybody in the world is helping us and we're doing OK,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   About 28 families spent the night in an emergency shelter in
Sparta Township. Steve Wille, a Red Cross volunteer who has lived
here for 30 years, said he'd never seen anything like Saturday's
storm.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've all seen sheets of rain for five, 10, 15 minutes. This
continued for hour after hour after hour after hour,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Yards in Sparta were covered with mud and a fast current of
brown water flowed down streets.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Preskar Earl said the combination of flooding and downed
trees diverted two ponds in her back yard into a stream that runs
behind her house.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was just water and trees and boulders coming everywhere,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   In Newton, water supply was a major concern as rushing water
took out the town's two water mains along the Sparta Glen, said
Town Manager Camille Furgiulele.
</P>
<P>
   Furgiulele said town officials had decided to tap a nearby water
well to alleviate the problem, but that the supplementary source
would only yield about 20 percent of the usual supply of 1 million
gallons a day.
</P>
<P>
   The well was put online just after 11 a.m. Officials also said
they were talking to the National Guard and some private companies
to see if additional water supplies could be trucked in.
</P>
<P>
   Repair crews were unable to reach the water mains because roads
were flooded and a bridge to access the area had washed out.
</P>
<P>
   Furgiulele said although there are only about 8,000 residents in
Newton, the county seat, up to 20,000 people work there.
</P>
<P>
   In nearby Franklin, Sussex County, water was still up to the
front porches of houses Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ''Seeing people row boats to their houses, that was pretty
crazy,'' said Josh Osowski, 26, of Newton, who was passing through
Franklin.
</P>
<P>
   In Jefferson Township, all roads were reopened Sunday except
Route 15 south. One of the three emergency shelters that had opened
Saturday was closed and many people were able to return to their
homes.
</P>
<P>
   A police dispatcher said things were getting back to normal
''slowly but surely.''
</P>
<P>
   Flooding lakes and rivers Saturday washed out bridges in
Jefferson Township and Ogdensburg, and caused road closures in
Morris and Sussex counties.
</P>
<P>
   In Sussex County alone, damages will reach millions of dollars,
estimated county Emergency Management Coordinator Eskil ''Skip''
Danielson. Four bridges were destroyed and several roads washed
out.
</P>
<P>
   About 250 customers of GPU Energy were without power Sunday
afternoon in Newton, Sparta and Flemington, said Ron Morano, a
company spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The energy company was planning to fly over the area to see if
there were any outages that had not yet been reported. Power had
been restored to most of the 10,000 customers who were without it
Saturday, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
