<BODY>
<HEADLINE> College students left in debt over painting  </HEADLINE>
	   By The Associated Press
<TEXT>
<P>
   Instead of painting the town red this summer, some college
students around the Northeast are finding that painting is putting
them in the red financially.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Friedman was among the college students who thought he had
found a dream job as a manager for University Painters of Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Friedman, a 19-year-old Avon resident who attends Johnson &AMP;
Wales University, was told he could manage his own business, earn a
profit of $5,000 to $13,000, and get a four-day cruise to the
Bahamas for painting homes with other college students. By
mid-summer, Friedman found himself thousands of dollars in debt,
his painters unpaid and liable to the Virginia company for $3,000
for failing to live up to his contract.
</P>
<P>
   ''Instead of having money for school, now I have none,''
Friedman said. ''I have no money, no job, and I've lost the entire
summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Other students, many recruited through campus employment
offices, are reporting similar problems, wishing they had never
become involved with University Painters, based in Alexandria.
</P>
<P>
   Joshua D. Jablon, the founder and president of University
Painters, said many students had successful experiences working for
his company. But he conceded problems occurred in New England,
saying the company might have made mistakes in recruiting.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is not for the meek. It's a hard, challenging job that
requires a lot more than the typical summer job,'' Jablon said.
''There's a lot of guys who are frustrated in New England.''
</P>
<P>
   Friedman, along with 23 other college students around New
England, was selected to be an ''outlet manager.'' He was to run a
small business, make estimates, hire and supervise painters.
</P>
<P>
   The managers all signed contracts saying if they quit or were
fired, they would have to pay University Painters $3,000.
</P>
<P>
   Students say they didn't read the contract closely or didn't
fully understand its provisions. Some conceded that they signed
even after their parents had raised red flags.
</P>
<P>
   At least 14 of the 24 student managers quit or were fired. Of
the 11 managers who spoke to the Hartford Courant, most reported
inadequate training and pay problems.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the students said University Painters delayed paying
their painters by claiming it did not receive the necessary
documents. Many painters quit as a result.
</P>
<P>
   Friedman, a sports management major, was fired on July 19. He
said he will file a complaint with the state Department of Labor
seeking its help in his dispute with University Painters.
</P>
<P>
   ''I guess I'm stupid for falling for it, but I tried to make it
work,'' Friedman said. ''I'm stuck with all my equipment. This
company needs to stop taking advantage of college kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Jablon said Friedman's painting crew will be paid and that any
houses left incomplete will be finished by his company.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will be happy to settle each and every situation,''
Friedman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
