<HEADLINE> Massachusetts tribe could claim land in Connecticut  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   KILLINGLY, Conn. (AP) - The petition of a Massachusetts Indian
tribe for federal recognition has town leaders in northeast
Connecticut preparing for possible land claims.
</P>
<P>
   The federal Bureau of Indian Affairs is expected to rule in
November on the petition of the Nipmuc Nation. Officials said they
expect that if the federal government grants the recognition, the
Nipmucs will file claim to more than 10,000 acres in Massachusetts,
just across Connecticut's border.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, representatives of the 10 member towns of the
Northeastern Connecticut Council of Governments asked the council's
attorney to check into whether the Nipmucs may have a legal claim
to land in Connecticut. The Nipmucs currently own 4 acres of land
in Thompson, about 200 yards from the border.
</P>
<P>
   Council Executive Director John Filchak said the council would
hold a ''preliminary and very general'' discussion of the Nipmuc
issue during its monthly meeting on Thursday. The council's member
towns include Brooklyn, Canterbury, Eastford, Thompson, Killingly,
Plainfield, Pomfret, Putnam, Sterling and Woodstock.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't know how directly or indirectly the Nipmuc land
claims affect our member towns,'' said Filchak. ''We still need
more specifics and need to see more documents on the issue.''
</P>
<P>
   William Gould, chairman of the Nipmuc Nation Tribal Council,
said his tribe has plans to claim land in Massachusetts, but
currently has no plans to claim any more land in Connecticut. Gould
said 45 percent of the tribe's 2,000 or so members live in this
state, about 50 percent live in Massachusetts and about 5 percent
live in Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   Woodstock First Selectman Ernest Wetzel said his town, Putnam
and Thompson all could be impacted by the recognition of the
Nipmucs.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is all very preliminary,'' he said. ''Right now, we know
there are many Nipmucs who have residency in the towns, but, once
they get tribal recognition, we don't know if they will make claims
on land, claims for reservations, or expect some concessions in the
towns.''
</P>
</TEXT>
