<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Schools show race disparity in discipline jccp </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - The percentage of minority students
suspended and expelled from school exceeds their representation in
many school districts in Connecticut, a new study shows.
</P>
<P>
   Minority students receive nearly half of all the suspensions and
expulsions statewide, but make up less than 1/3 of the student
population, the state's disciplinary offense report found. The
numbers were reported to the state for the 1998-99 school year.
</P>
<P>
   In Norwalk, minorities make up 50 percent of the population but
account for 69 percent of punished offenses. In West Haven, 39
percent of students are minorities while accounting for 52 percent
of the cases. In Ansonia, minorities make up 28 percent of the
population and 42 percent of the discipline cases.
</P>
<P>
   Minority advocates expressed concern over the finding, while
some school officials demanded a recount.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think there is a perception that black kids need a harsher
discipline than whiter students,'' said Wayne Winston, co-chairman
of the Bridgeport education committee of the National Association
for the Advancement of Colored People.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Orfield, a Harvard professor and leading desegregation
expert, said he is disturbed but not surprised by the rate at which
minority students in Connecticut are disciplined.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's part of a long-established pattern,'' Orfield said.
</P>
<P>
   A June report by the Civil Rights Project, which Orfield
co-directs, found that while black children represent 17 percent of
public school enrollment, they comprise 32 percent of suspensions.
Another report, issued by the U.S. Department of Education in 1997,
found that almost 25 percent of all black male students were
suspended at least once over a four-year period.
</P>
<P>
   Susanne Murphy, assistant school superintendent in Ansonia, said
officials would not tolerate any evidence of unfair discipline.
</P>
<P>
   ''If differentiated discipline should emerge, we would instantly
step in to see it not happen,'' Murphy said.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy said the discipline disparity is a concern.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't have the answer,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Stratford School Superintendent Raymond O'Connell also couldn't
explain why minorities are disciplined more often than whites in
Stratford. Stratford officials contend the figures they sent to the
state are wrong, possibly because they confused the code for white
and Hispanic students.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Murphy, spokesman for the state Department of Education,
said the purpose of the report is to give local districts and the
state Legislature a better understanding of what's happening in
schools.
</P>
<P>
   ''Obviously the numbers do raise concerns that we expect school
districts will address,'' Murphy said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-13-00 1318 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
