<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Guardhouse Decks Berlin Wall  </HEADLINE>
By BURT HERMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- The guardhouse went up again at Berlin's infamous
Checkpoint Charlie on Sunday, and parts of the Berlin Wall are to
be rebuilt at the border crossing where Cold War powers faced off
just yards apart.
</P>
<P>
   Berlin isn't about to become a divided city again. This time,
the guards wearing U.S. and British military uniforms were just
Germans in costume. They were participating in the unveiling of a
guardhouse rebuilt to stand as a reminder to future generations of
the barrier that divided a country -- and Europe and the world along
with it.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our duty is to maintain and salvage what was once here,'' said
Rainer Hildebrandt, head of the Museum at Checkpoint Charlie and a
leading force behind preserving the memory of the scar that ran
through Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   It was exactly 39 years ago Sunday that construction began on
the Wall. East German leaders called it an ''Anti-Fascist
Protection Barrier'' -- although the real goal of the Wall was to
stop the thousands of their citizens who were leaving for the West.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Wall went up, people could travel freely across
Berlin, and many who lived in one part of the city worked in the
other. That all changed after Aug. 13, 1961, when, without any
warning, East German soldiers began stringing lengths of barbed
wire and building barriers across the city.
</P>
<P>
   In the years that followed, nearly 1,000 people died trying to
cross the border between the divided Germany, including 235 killed
at the Berlin Wall.
</P>
<P>
   Checkpoint Charlie -- so named because it was the third
checkpoint in the city after Alpha and Bravo -- got its first
guardhouse on Sept. 22, 1961. In the months afterward, both the
United States and Soviet Union stationed their tanks there on what
became the front line in the Cold War, known for its trademark
''You are leaving the American sector'' sign.
</P>
<P>
   Those tanks wouldn't move until after Nov. 9, 1989. That was the
day East Germans streamed through the border after the government
decided to lift the travel restrictions that had been in place for
more than 28 years.
</P>
<P>
   After it fell, Berliners were more than eager to tear down all
signs of the Wall. Thousands of tourists with hammers chipped
pieces away, and much of the Wall was ground up and used to make
roads. The previous guardhouse at Checkpoint Charlie was removed
June 22, 1990 as diplomats from the Allied powers looked on.
</P>
<P>
   Now, more than 10 years after the Wall fell, there have been
increasing efforts to try and preserve the memory of the most
visible manifestation of the Iron Curtain.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the new white, wooden guardhouse that stands in
an island in the road at Checkpoint Charlie, the museum hopes to
restore elements of the entire barrier system, which included tank
traps, dog runs and the no man's land in between the Wall's two
sides.
</P>
<P>
   Restoration work also has begun across town on one of the
largest remaining strips of the Wall, the so-called East Side
Gallery. After 1989, artists there decorated what was once the
untouchable eastern side of the barrier with pictorial odes to
peace.
</P>
<P>
   The new Checkpoint Charlie guardhouse ''must always remind us
how easy it is to divide people, and how long it takes and what
effort it costs to bring them together again,'' Eduard
Shevardnadze, president of Georgia and a former Soviet foreign
minister, said in a letter sent to the Sunday ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Maj. Nigel Dunkley, military attache to the British Embassy,
remembered the hard stares he received from East German border
officers and the cameras that watched his every move when passing
through the border.
</P>
<P>
   ''The younger generation does not have any concept of the
oppressive atmosphere,'' he said after the unveiling. ''We tend to
forget how terrible it was and it's not a bad idea to remind
people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-13-00 1348 </TRAILER>
