<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Connecticut delegates get front seat at Democratic convention  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LOS ANGELES (AP) - Connecticut's delegation to the Democratic
National Convention this week has suddenly found itself taking a
front seat after the selection of Senator Joseph Lieberman as Vice
President Al Gore's running mate.
</P>
<P>
   The state's 67 delegates originally were placed at the back of
the convention floor. But with Connecticut's junior senator now
Gore's vice presidential running mate, the delegates have been
moved to the front, next to Gore's home state of Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   ''We thought we'd be in the backwater, and now we're the stars;
no, the second stars,'' said Dennis O'Neil, an alternate from
Litchfield.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neil is hoping to brandish a replica of the UConn women's
basketball team's NCAA championship trophy in front of the
neighboring Tennessee delegates. The University of Tennessee's Lady
Volunteers lost to the Lady Huskies in the tournament final in
March.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut is expected to cast 67 votes this week for Gore as
the party's nominee for president, including 17 ballots from
supporters of Bill Bradley. Bradley lost to Gore in the Democratic
primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Paindiris, chairman of the Bradley campaign in Connecticut
and a Glastonbury delegate, said he is behind the ticket. One
reason is Lieberman.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are more energized than ever before,'' Paindiris said.
''We're part of the action. It's almost like being a Tennessee
delegate.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman's elevated status has given O'Neil a reason to care
about the political process again.
</P>
<P>
   ''That the daughter of Holocaust survivors can stand on the
threshold of a dream, it can only happen here,'' O'Neil said,
referring to Lieberman's wife, Hadassah.
</P>
<P>
   William Moriarty, a Waterbury resident attending his first
convention, said the event has taken on new meaning.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've moved up to the front of the pack now,'' Moriarty said.
''He's No. 2 on the ticket.''
</P>
<P>
   The Connecticut delegates will have their choice of star-studded
parties. They've received hundreds of invitations, from a concert
featuring Barbara Streisand, Whoopi Goldberg and Boyz II Men to a
tribute to Lieberman tonight sponsored by the Interstate Natural
Gas Association of America.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is going to be one of the most exciting weeks of my
life,'' Moriarty said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
