<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 14:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ivory Coast Looks Worriedly Ahead  </HEADLINE>
By TIM SULLIVAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABIDJAN, Ivory Coast (AP) -- When soldiers here staged their
Christmas Eve coup, they announced themselves by holding up a
supermarket, robbing residents and cruising this sprawling city in
looted four-wheel-drives, firing automatic weapons into the air.
</P>
<P>
   Eight months later, the general those soldiers brought to power
remembers the putsch as a smooth transition -- a ''velvet
revolution,'' as he puts it -- all the while calling for calm as the
increasingly uneasy West African nation moves toward upcoming
presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
   The pleas from Gen. Robert Guei may not be enough.
</P>
<P>
   Ivory Coast -- once an island of stability in one of the world's
most troubled regions -- faces a conjunction of political and
military turmoil in coming weeks that some fear could lead to
widespread unrest, and perhaps even tear the country apart.
</P>
<P>
   In a dingy, concrete meeting hall in the working class
neighborhood of Abobo, hundreds of people pumped their fists in the
air on a recent evening, shouting support for the man they want as
Ivory Coast's next president: opposition leader Alassane Dramane
Ouattara.
</P>
<P>
   The rally was illegal, since campaigning is not allowed until
two weeks before the Sept. 17 presidential vote. Hulking security
guards in warmup jackets eye the sea of taxi drivers, housekeepers
and construction workers streaming into the hall while scanning the
street for soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the tension, Ouattara's candidacy remains in question.
</P>
<P>
   A last-minute amendment to the country's new constitution
stipulates that both parents of presidential candidates must be
''of Ivorian origin.'' The change is widely believed to be aimed at
excluding Ouattara, a former prime minister and top official with
the International Monetary Fund whose opponents insist his parents
were from neighboring Burkina Faso.
</P>
<P>
   The issue goes beyond presidential politics, reflecting a
complex history of religious, ethnic and geographic suspicion
between northerners -- most of them Muslims who support Ouattara --
and the southern Christians who long dominated the Ivorian
government.
</P>
<P>
   To Ouattara's many supporters, his exclusion is unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   ''It would completely divide the country,'' said Brahima Camara,
20, taking a break at the rally.
</P>
<P>
   And if he can't run?
</P>
<P>
   ''We'll have a civil war,'' he said simply, echoing a comment
made repeatedly by Ouattara's supporters. ''I want to avoid that,
but he should be a candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   While the possibility of war is fiercely debated, the idea would
have been dismissed just a couple of years ago. Ivory Coast was the
star of West Africa, a nation with 40 years of stable civilian
government and an economy that dwarfed its neighbors'.
</P>
<P>
   But things changed quickly here. Battered by plummeting prices
for its main exports, cocoa and coffee, the economy faltered.
</P>
<P>
   With jobs disappearing, Ivory Coast's welcoming attitude toward
immigrants -- some 40 percent of its 19 million residents come from
elsewhere -- began souring. The now-ousted president, Henri Konan
Bedie, launched a series of ethnically divisive policies.
</P>
<P>
   Out of this brew came the December coup d'etat.
</P>
<P>
   Although initially popular among Ivorians, who were weary of the
Bedie regime's alleged corruption and ethnic favoritism, the junta
has left many people disillusioned.
</P>
<P>
   Guei took control promising to heal the country's ethnic rifts.
But the questions over Ouattara's candidacy have instead made them
worse.
</P>
<P>
   And Guei, who stepped into the post-coup spotlight pledging to
quickly step down, now has a well-oiled political machine seeking
his presidential nomination -- by the former ruling party that his
soldiers forced from power.
</P>
<P>
   Like much in Ivory Coast these days, Guei's ambitions reflect
the overlap of military and political concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Guei's moves to remain in power have alienated some of his
military allies, according to a report in the Abidjan-based
independent newspaper Le Jour, which said some junta members are
asking that Guei resign if he wants to run in the elections.
</P>
<P>
   Soldiers, meanwhile, say the security forces are increasingly
fractured along political lines, with various groups backing Guei,
Ouattara and the ousted Bedie, who vows to return for the elections
from his forced exile in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Twice since the coup, unrest in the ranks over unpaid bonuses
has flared into mutiny. Tensions rose sharply after a two-day July
rebellion, when rioting soldiers looted banks and stores. Weeks
later, the promised bonuses remain unpaid, and soldiers say anger
is bubbling again.
</P>
<P>
   While such divisions are unsettling to many Ivorians, Guei's
supporters use them for political gain, arguing that only a general
can keep Ivory Coast from devolving into anarchy.
</P>
<P>
   ''Thanks to Gen. Guei, we have avoided a bloodbath,'' said Balla
Keita, the general's political adviser. ''He's someone who can keep
the soldiers in the barracks ... Ouattara can't do that. No one
else can do that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-13-00 1411 </TRAILER>
