<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinian State Might Be Delayed  </HEADLINE>
By MAAMOUN YOUSSEF
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- Egypt's president said Sunday that
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat may put off plans to declare an
independent Palestinian state on Sept. 13, the deadline for a final
Israeli-Palestinian peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ''This may happen, I don't know and I can't say this, but I
believe the delay may take place,'' President Hosni Mubarak told
reporters as he inaugurated a scientific research center. ''We
don't want any clash between the two sides.''
</P>
<P>
   Arafat repeatedly has said he will declare an independent state
Sept. 13, and Egypt has been among Arab nations to say that they
would recognize a Palestinian state whenever Arafat chooses to
declare it.
</P>
<P>
   However, Palestinian officials have said that Arab countries,
under pressure from the United States, urged Arafat to postpone the
declaration of independence to give another chance to talks with
Israel. Assistant Secretary of State Edward Walker has been
briefing Arab leaders on U.S. positions and urging them not to do
anything to lessen chances for a resumption of negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat said in Jerusalem that the
Palestinians are reluctant to change the deadline because they do
not want negotiations with Israel to go on ''without a ceiling,
open-ended.''
</P>
<P>
   ''My instructions from Arafat, and this we've conveyed to the
Israelis, are to reach an agreement with the Israelis no later than
Sept. 13,'' Erekat said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But Palestinian legislator Ziad Abu Zayyad said the decision on
a date for a declaration was not final. ''The PLO's ruling body
will meet at the end of August, early September to make a final
decision on the date for a declaration,'' Zayyad told Israel radio.
</P>
<P>
   Mubarak, a key mediator in the Mideast peace process, said a
deal between Israel and the Palestinians before the deadline was
possible -- but his words were not optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ''The issue needs hard and combined efforts and, God willing, I
hope we will strike a deal, but I can't say if that will be before
or after Sept 13,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Shlomo Ben-Ami, Israel's acting foreign minister, said in a
telephone interview with Israeli television that he thinks Arafat
will not declare a state by that deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ''If there will be a unilateral declaration, it will be very
harmful for the peace process,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak is scheduled to visit Jordan
on Wednesday for talks with King Abdullah II, who has been trying
to bridge the gaps between the Palestinians and the Israelis, a
government official and the Israeli Embassy announced.
</P>
<P>
   In July, a two-week summit with Arafat and Barak collapsed over
the issue of Jerusalem's fate.
</P>
<P>
   Barak offered the Palestinians limited control over parts of
east Jerusalem, but Arafat held firm on Palestinians' demand for
full sovereignty over the traditionally Arab area.
</P>
<P>
   East Jerusalem contains sites holy to Muslims, Christians and
Jews, including the third-holiest shrine in the Islamic world.
Israel has long said that Jerusalem must remain united under
Israeli sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking support for the Palestinians' position, Arafat made a
brief stop in Pakistan on Sunday en route to China.
</P>
<P>
   He was to meet Pakistan's army ruler, Gen. Pervez Musharraf.
Pakistan is a longtime supporter of the Palestinians and does not
recognize the state of Israel or let its citizens travel there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-13-00 1429 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000813.0042 </DOCNO>
