<DOCNO> APW20000813.0043 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 14:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hollow Man, Cowboys Top Box Office  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID GERMAIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Curmudgeon astronauts and an invisible maniac
topped the movie marquees, with scab football players and
May-December lovers close behind.
</P>
<P>
   The invisible scientist thriller ''Hollow Man'' and the
geriatric NASA adventure ''Space Cowboys'' tied for first place at
the weekend box office with $13.1 million apiece, according to
studio estimates Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The rankings could change when final numbers are released
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hollow Man,'' starring Kevin Bacon and Elisabeth Shue, debuted
at No. 1 while Clint Eastwood's ''Space Cowboys'' opened in third
place a week earlier. But ''Space Cowboys'' held more strongly in
its second weekend, its take dropping just 28 percent, compared
with a 50 percent drop for ''Hollow Man.''
</P>
<P>
   It was an unusual weekend, with no film dominating and the top
seven movies bunched within a few million dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ''Autumn in New York,'' the Richard Gere-Winona Ryder
tearjerker, debuted at No. 3 with $11.5 million. Keanu Reeves and
Gene Hackman's ''The Replacements,'' a comedy about misfit players
during a football strike, opened in fourth place with $11.1
million.
</P>
<P>
   Two holdovers were No. 5 and 6, ''Nutty Professor II: The
Klumps'' with $10.3 million and ''What Lies Beneath'' with $9.8
million. The supernatural tale ''Bless the Child,'' starring Kim
Basinger and Jimmy Smits, premiered at No. 7 with $9.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   August typically is a slow month for Hollywood. With summer
waning, films cluster together and post smaller grosses as
''blockbuster fatigue sets in,'' said Paul Dergarabedian, president
of Exhibitor Relations, which tracks movie-ticket sales.
</P>
<P>
   ''This weekend was sort of a horse race. A slow horse race, but
still a horse race,'' Dergarabedian said. ''Unless you have films
like 'Sixth Sense' from last August that grab the national
consciousness, it's tough to have any record-breaking grosses.''
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the top 12 films grossed $97.7 million, down 13.7
percent from last year and continuing a summer slump behind 1999's
record summer revenues of $3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ''Autumn in New York'' posted the best per-theater average among
wide-release films at $5,100 in 2,255 cinemas. That compared to
$4,621 in 2,835 theaters for ''Space Cowboys'' and $4,432 in 2,956
cinemas for ''Hollow Man.''
</P>
<P>
   Gere and Ryder's film debuted solidly even though distributor
MGM chose not to screen it for reviewers beforehand, usually a sign
the movie is a bomb.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Gleason, MGM head of distribution, said the studio
scrapped advance screenings because of the somber subject matter, a
romance between a man and a dying younger woman.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our best judgment was that it would have gotten disappointing
reviews basically saying that even though it's beautifully
photographed, it's really a downer,'' Gleason said. ''This is a
movie that plays to upscale audiences who are the ones most
affected by adverse reviews.''
</P>
<P>
   DreamWorks' ''What Lies Beneath'' climbed to $112.1 million, the
10th movie released this year to hit $100 million. The studio's
''Chicken Run,'' with $99.9 million, is expected to pass that mark
Monday and surpass ''The Prince of Egypt'' later this week as
DreamWorks' highest-grossing animated movie.
</P>
<P>
   In limited release, cult director John Waters scored an
impressive opening for his madcap assault on Hollywood filmmaking,
''Cecil B. DeMented,'' starring Stephen Dorff and Melanie Griffith.
The movie took in $130,000 at nine theaters for a $14,444 average.
</P>
<P>
   Brenda Blethyn's marijuana comedy ''Saving Grace'' had a good
second weekend with $358,000 at 35 theaters and a $10,229 average.
Distributor Fine Line plans to expand the film to nearly 300
theaters next weekend and add a few hundred more later.
</P>
<P>
   Estimated ticket sales for Friday through Sunday at North
American theaters, according to Exhibitor Relations Co. Inc.:
</P>
<P>
   1. (tie). ''Hollow Man,'' $13.1 million.	   1. (tie). ''Space Cowboys,''
$13.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   3. ''Autumn in New York,'' $11.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   4. ''The Replacements,'' $11.1 million.
</P>
<P>
