<HEADLINE> Crowd in Malaysia Backs Anwar  </HEADLINE>
By ALVIN UNG
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) -- Nearly 1,000 people gathered
outside a maximum-security prison on the outskirts of Kuala Lumpur
on Sunday to demand freedom for jailed former deputy prime minister
Anwar Ibrahim.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstration was the fourth anti-government rally since a
high court judge on Tuesday convicted Anwar of sodomy and sentenced
him to nine years in prison atop the six years he is serving for
corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Anwar, who was sacked by Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad and
arrested in September 1998, denies all the charges, saying they
were trumped up by his political enemies to end his career.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of riot police gripping shields and armed with tear gas
launchers stood in formation within the compound in Sungai Buloh,
37 miles north of the capital, where Anwar is imprisoned.
</P>
<P>
   ''Freedom for Anwar!'' cried the men, women and children, who
released a half-dozen pigeons and doves, along with scores of
balloons, into the stormy sky. ''God is great! Freedom to the
people!''
</P>
<P>
   They sang patriotic songs, yelled ''Reformasi,'' the cry for
political reform, and demanded the resignation of Mahathir.
</P>
<P>
   They held up banners reading ''Happy Birthday Anwar!'' and
''Liberate the judiciary!'' Anwar turned 53 on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Anwar has repeatedly lambasted the judiciary, accusing it of
allowing itself to be manipulated by his one-time mentor, Mahathir,
who has ruled Malaysia for nearly two decades.
</P>
<P>
   Mahathir criticized other countries for saying that the judicial
system in Malaysia is not good, a news report said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ''The U.S. is the same too,'' he said. ''... The same thing
happened in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Countries who issued statements condemning Malaysia over the
recent verdict against Anwar include the United States, Canada,
Australia, and New Zealand, the national news agency Bernama said.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition activists have announced plans for a rally in the
country's biggest sports stadium, on the outskirts of Kuala Lumpur,
and to launch a national movement against Mahathir, starting in the
opposition-controlled states in northern Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
   Several police trucks and a water cannon truck were on the scene
Sunday, but there was no attempt to disperse the crowd, which
demonstrated for an hour and then drove off in a convoy of more
than 100 vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel invigorated by all the support,'' said Anwar's wife,
Azizah Ismail, who was at the prison with her four daughters.
</P>
<P>
   An opposition leader in the Democratic Action Party, Lim Kit
Siang, called the verdict ''a cruel and unconscionable political
persecution'' and urged Malaysians to vote Mahathir out.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is something very dark in the Malaysian national soul
which is completely alien to the most rudimentary notions of
decency and justice,'' he said in a statement. ''This corruption of
the national soul must be purged.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
