<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Milosevic's Challenger Blasts U.S.  </HEADLINE>
By JOVANA GEC
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- President Slobodan Milosevic's main
challenger at upcoming national elections in Yugoslavia slammed the
United States on Sunday, saying no Serb should ever forget last
year's NATO bombing of the country.
</P>
<P>
   While naming Milosevic as the main culprit for Serbia's hardship
in the past decade, Vojislav Kostunica, the presidential candidate
of most of the pro-democracy parties in the upcoming election, said
Washington has been ''evil'' to the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   ''Those who bombed Serbia could have avoided March 24,''
Kostunica said, referring to the first day of NATO's 1999 attacks.
''Their responsibility is somewhat bigger because their power is
greater.''
</P>
<P>
   Kostunica's comments during a meeting of his Serbian Democratic
Party reflect a widespread anti-American sentiment among Serbs, who
believe Washington's policy of imposing sanctions was unjust,
despite Milosevic's responsibility for bloodshed in the former
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Kostunica, considered a moderate nationalist who has stayed out
of various failed opposition deals, enjoys the greatest support by
far among Serbs, recent independent polls suggest.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts fear, however, that Milosevic will rig the Sept.
24 national elections for president and parliament.
</P>
<P>
   In Podgorica, Montenegro's pro-Western leader Milo Djukanovic
said in comments published Sunday that the upcoming elections were
a farce and that his government would resist outside pressure to
take part.
</P>
<P>
   Djukanovic, whose tiny republic and Serbia make up Yugoslavia,
told a gathering of Montenegrin diaspora on Saturday that the
elections only serve to give ''legitimacy to the Belgrade
dictatorship,'' Montenegro's official Montena fax news agency said.
</P>
<P>
   Djukanovic, a former Milosevic ally, has been taking steps
toward independence, raising fears of Milosevic's armed
intervention in Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   Montenegro's leadership has cited recent constitutional changes
which downgrade the republic's position in the federation as the
reason for the election boycott.
</P>
<P>
   Djukanovic has rejected appeals by U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright and Serb pro-democracy forces to reconsider his
boycott decision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
