<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 15:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Burial Spawns Thai Tourism  </HEADLINE>
By MICOOL BROOKE
<TEXT>
<P>
   KHUN YUAM, Thailand (AP) -- As World War II dragged to a bloody
close in 1945, Imperial Japan's 15th army was in retreat from
Burma. About 20,000 wounded and exhausted soldiers died during the
long march home.
</P>
<P>
   Their death -- and their memories -- are bringing unexpected
prosperity to this dirt-poor border village: It was here, at a
Buddhist temple-turned-field hospital, where many of the Japanese
soldiers breathed their last.
</P>
<P>
   A joint Japanese-Thai excavation program to find the remains,
plus pilgrimages by Japanese veterans and their families to honor
the war dead, have spawned a tourism industry catering especially
to the Japanese, the local police chief said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Because of its fascinating history, Khun Yuam is on the road
to becoming ... like the bridge on the River Kwai,'' said Lt. Col.
Cherdchai Chomchavat, referring to the bridge on the infamous Death
Railway that Japanese forces built using Allied prisoners as
laborers.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands were buried in and around Khun Yuam, which has
remained virtually unchanged over the last five decades -- a
one-street village of about 100 families, mostly subsistence
farmers living in thatch-roofed bamboo huts set amid lush wild
vegetation.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese officials first surveyed the Khun Yuam area in 1978,
when they excavated 362 remains near the border with Burma, now
known as Myanmar. A joint survey with the Thai Fine Arts Department
conducted in 1998 estimated that as many as 7,000 remains are
present at 39 locations in the district.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, about two dozen Japanese make the arduous trip every
weekend to Khun Yuam, 500 miles northwest of the Thai capital of
Bangkok. They first travel by train or by road to the town of Mae
Hong Son, then complete the remaining 40-mile journey by taxis or
buses on a potholed road.
</P>
<P>
   Most make a day trip, though a 12-room guesthouse opened in the
village earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   To commemorate ''Victory Japan Day,'' the day Japan ceased
hostilities in 1945, relatives plan private services Tuesday at the
Japanese War Museum in Khun Yuam. The museum houses a large
collection of war relics, including rifles, swords, helmets, bugles
and heavy machine guns.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have nothing interesting other than World War II military
history and the skeletons of dead soldiers,'' said Cherdchai, the
police chief, who also is the museum's curator.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of the village is the sprawling 100-year-old Muay
To temple complex, which housed the Japanese 15th Army's field
hospital. The makeshift facility treated soldiers who marched
through hundreds of miles of jungle to reach the sanctuary of
Thailand, a wartime ally, after the failed invasion of India and
the debacle in Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
   Around the temple -- a renovated modern structure of gold painted
slanted roof -- are shrines built by the Japanese relatives. Most
are gravestone-style memorials dedicated to ''warriors of heaven,''
each surrounded by a metal gate.
</P>
<P>
   Cherdchai said the construction of the shrines generated
employment in the village. Some Japanese are also funding charity
programs and student scholarships, he said.
</P>
<P>
   War veteran Nagase Takashi, 83, spent $15,000 of his pension
this year to build a ''Stars and Dew'' temple at Khun Yuam to honor
fallen Japanese soldiers, including his brother-in-law. The temple
is a spartan prayer room, the far end dominated by a large metallic
statue of a sitting Buddha.
</P>
<P>
   Takashi, a resident of Kurashiki city, told the AP during a
recent visit that he was compelled to do something to honor the
15th Army's war dead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-13-00 1524 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000813.0048 </DOCNO>
