<HEADLINE> Nobel Winners Lead 'Night of Peace'  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOURDES, France (AP) -- Former Nobel Peace Prize winners gathered
Sunday in southwest France to celebrate a ''Night of Peace'' that
was expected to draw tens of thousands of visitors, pilgrims and
international humanitarians.
</P>
<P>
   Argentinean laureate Adolfo Perez Esquivel, Cambodian Tum
Chanareth and Mairead Maguire, an Irish peace activist, were among
the former Nobel prize winners that shared the vision of peace and
nonviolence for children worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Humanitarians and religious figures were also scheduled to
address the crowd gathered in Lourdes, the site of a Catholic
healing shrine which draws more than 4 million visitors a year.
</P>
<P>
   The event was organized by the French group, Appeal by the Nobel
Peace Prize Laureates, to promote a United Nations resolution which
calls for peace for the children in the world in the new
millennium's first decade, the group said.
</P>
</TEXT>
