<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Men Held for Weapons in Yugoslavia  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Ten men were detained after French
peacekeepers discovered a cache of grenades, ammunition and radios
in northern Kosovo, NATO-led peacekeepers said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The weapons were found Saturday in the divided city of Kosovska
Mitrovica, where speculation that the United Nations plans to take
over a Serb-controlled lead smelting plant has heightened tensions
in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   French peacekeepers who patrol the predominantly Serb northern
sector of the city seized the weapons after noticing a man with a
two-way radio standing outside a shed.
</P>
<P>
   The peacekeepers cordoned off the area, a U.N statement said. A
search of the premises unearthed the grenades, ammunition and
radios.
</P>
<P>
   Ten people were then turned over to U.N. police. Maj. Craig T.
Snow, a spokesman for NATO-led peacekeepers, could not immediately
confirm whether they were Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Tensions have risen in the industrial city over the fate of the
plant in the nearby town of Zvecan, just north of Kosovska
Mitrovica. Last week, U.N. officials said that the plant was
spewing pollution into the air, raising lead levels to 200 times
the accepted World Health Organization norms. The United Nations
immediately launched a public awareness campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In a rare moment of solidarity, Serb and ethnic Albanian leaders
joined with U.N. personnel to publicly have their blood tested.
Kosovo Serb leader Oliver Ivanovic claimed the lead scare is an
excuse for the United Nations to take over the Zvecan plant.
</P>
<P>
   With Serbs and ethnic Albanians living in the same community,
Kosovska Mitrovica is the most ethnically mixed city in Kosovo --
and the most violence-prone.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of ethnic Albanians were killed by Serb forces during
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic's 18-month crackdown against
separatists in Kosovo. After NATO bombing forced the Serb troops to
withdraw last year, ethnic Albanians began attacking Serbs as
revenge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-13-00 1528 </TRAILER>
