<HEADLINE> Rebels Kill Russian Convoy Soldiers  </HEADLINE>
By YURI BAGROV
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAZRAN, Russia (AP) -- Rebel fighters ambushed a Russian convoy
near the Chechen capital, killing three soldiers and wounding 10,
officials said Sunday, a day after the top pro-Moscow leader in
Chechnya claimed rebel forces were no longer a major threat.
</P>
<P>
   Two armored personnel carriers were passing through the village
of Prigorodnoye just outside Grozny on Saturday when rebels
attacked, an official with the pro-Russian Chechen government said
on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Russian troops returned fire, and the battle continued for 40
minutes, the official said. It was not known if the rebels suffered
losses.
</P>
<P>
   The ambush came a day after Russia's top civilian leader in
Chechnya, Mufti Akhmad Kadyrov, claimed the rebels were too
scattered to pose a threat to Russian troops.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels in the breakaway republic have refrained from
launching major attacks for weeks, instead relying on ambushes and
other guerrilla tactics to wear down the Russians. They have
acknowledged weapons shortages, but show little sign of giving up
their fight for independence.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians pushed into Chechnya last September after
withdrawing at the end of a 1994-96 war. But they have yet to take
back the southern third of the republic, where mountains and
forests provide ample cover for the rebels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
