<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reformist Writers Detained in Iran  </HEADLINE>
By ALI AKBAR DAREINI
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) -- Two pro-reform Iranian writers were arrested
just as they were being honored by their peers as the best in their
fields, reports said Sunday. The imprisonments brought the number
of writers detained to five in eight days.
</P>
<P>
   Ebrahim Nabavi was on his way to jail Saturday at the time his
name was being called out as best satirist at an awards ceremony
honoring Iranian media, said Karim Arqandehpour, deputy head of the
Press Guild Association.
</P>
<P>
   Nabavi, who had written for several now-banned reformist
newspapers, was interrogated Saturday and ordered jailed by the
judge of the hard-line press court, Saeed Mortazavi, the daily
Hamshahri reported.
</P>
<P>
   Mohammad Ghoochani was jailed Sunday, a day after he was honored
as best political writer. Ghoochani, who wrote for the now-banned
Asr-e-Azadegan, was summoned to court Saturday. He was seen Sunday
being led from court to prison.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is not a press festival. This is a press mourning. There
is nothing to celebrate,'' the daily Iran newspaper quoted Rajabali
Mazrouei as saying, presumably at the awards ceremony. Mazrouei is
a lawmaker and a leading member of the Islamic Iran Participation
Front, Iran's largest reformist party.
</P>
<P>
   Another liberal writer, Ahmad Zeidabadi, was supposed to be at
the awards ceremony as a member of the panel of journalists who
acted as judges. He was jailed Aug. 7, one of three other writers
detained recently.
</P>
<P>
   Since April, 25 newspapers -- all but one pro-reform -- have been
closed down and more than two dozen reformist writers jailed. Most
are being held in Tehran's Evin Prison on the charge of ''insulting
Islamic sanctities.''
</P>
<P>
   Nabavi, whose books are highly popular in Iran, was detained for
a month in September 1998 for his critical satirical writings.
</P>
<P>
   The judiciary also summoned Culture Minister Ataollah Mohajerani
to court Saturday to answer questions related to expenses made by
his ministry in unfinished cultural projects, IRNA reported.
Mohajerani is reviled by hard-liners, who tried to impeach him last
year over the press freedoms he had granted.
</P>
<P>
   Hard-liners have been fighting a popular reform movement led by
President Mohammad Khatami. The reformists won control of
parliament in February elections, but hard-liners run the
judiciary, military and the broadcast network.
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday, the parliament, or Majlis, which was scheduled to
debate lifting restrictions on press freedoms, was ordered by
hard-line supreme leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei not to amend the
press law, resulting in scuffles, shouts and a fight in open
session.
</P>
<P>
   Also Sunday, 161 members of the 290-seat Majlis signed a letter
pledging that reforms would continue.
</P>
<P>
   ''We assure the nation that the recent controversies will not
affect the will of the committed people of Islamic Iran for the
continuation of reforms, and that we, as your representatives,
advise and warn opportunist and reactionary currents to give up
efforts to discourage the people from pursuing reforms,'' said the
letter, obtained by The Associated Press.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-13-00 1535 </TRAILER>
