<HEADLINE> VP Vote To Test Paraguay Democracy  </HEADLINE>
By KEVIN GRAY
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) -- Paraguayans dipped their forefingers
in ink Sunday and voted for a vice president to serve beside a
hugely unpopular -- and unelected -- president.
</P>
<P>
   The special, one-office election was seen as a test to this
South American country's shaky democracy. The office has been empty
since Vice President Luis Argana was gunned down in the street in
March 1999.
</P>
<P>
   In the political chaos that followed his slaying, Luis Gonzalez
Macchi was thrust into the presidency and has since seen his
popularity plummet amid economic recession.
</P>
<P>
   Some 2 million Paraguayans were choosing from three candidates,
and election officials reported no incidents during the early
voting hours on a chilly and cloudy winter day.
</P>
<P>
   Pre-election polls showed the two leading candidates running
even: Julio Cesar Franco, 48, of the opposition Liberal party, and
Argana's 43-year-old son, Felix, of the ruling Colorado Party. The
third candidate, plastics artist Ricardo Buman, is considered a
long shot. He comes from the nascent Humanist Party.
</P>
<P>
   It is the first time in Paraguay's history that a vice president
will be chosen outside of a presidential election and opposition
members believe they have their best chance in years to break the
stranglehold of the Colorado Party, which has governed Paraguay
since 1947.
</P>
<P>
   Argana, an architect and Asuncion city councilman, voted Sunday
morning after visiting his father's tomb. He has cast himself as a
potentially stabilizing force in the troubled administration of
Macchi, the former Senate president who took office after Raul
Cubas resigned as president in the wake of Argana's death. Cubas
was suspected of being involved in Argana's killing.
</P>
<P>
   Macchi's popularity has dipped to less than 20 percent as
Paraguay struggles through a grinding recession.
</P>
<P>
   Argana supporters have suggested his election to office would be
a first step toward justice for his father's death. Argana's murder
remains unsolved, although a Paraguayan judge has accused Lino
Oviedo, an army chief and former political ally of Cubas, of being
the mastermind of the murder.
</P>
<P>
   Franco, a doctor, has suggested that he would work to have
Macchi removed from office.
</P>
<P>
   After casting his vote in downtown Asuncion, Franco
enthusiastically flashed his ink-stained forefinger to supporters.
Voters are required to dip their fingers in ink after voting in
order to prevent fraud.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
