<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Criticized on Neo-Nazis  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- The leader of Germany's Jewish
community accused German politicians and society Sunday of not
doing enough to fight neo-Nazis, urging more involvement from
parents and stronger action against far-right Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   ''What was before was too little,'' Paul Spiegel, president of
the Central Council of Jews in Germany, said at a ceremony honoring
the anniversary of his predecessor Ignatz Bubis' death.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before he died a year ago, Bubis had lamented in an
interview that he had failed to do enough to bring Germans and Jews
together. Although Bubis' remarks were viewed at the time as overly
pessimistic, Spiegel told an audience of 700 people at the Jewish
community center in Frankfurt that Bubis was a ''visionary.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We didn't let ourselves dream that a half-century after the
Holocaust it would be so difficult for the democratic German
society to resist right-extremism,'' Spiegel said. ''Before his
death, Bubis recognized this more clearly than we did then.''
</P>
<P>
   Spiegel appealed to parents in Germany to speak to their
children about the threat of neo-Nazis. When parents don't speak
out against violence aimed at foreigners, ''they make it all too
easy to look away and encourage by their silence,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Jewish leader also called for authorities to combat hate
sites on the Internet with the same vigilance with which they
pursue child pornography.
</P>
<P>
   German Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer also called for more
vigilance.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is not acceptable and must be fought with every force and
every legal instrument,'' he said in an interview Sunday in the
Italian newspaper Corriere della Sera.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, there were continued reports of incidents connected
to neo-Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   Five skinheads, aged 18 to 25, were arrested in the southern
city of Konstanz after an attack on two Turkish men, one of whom
was thrown into a lake. The two victims, ages 21 and 22, suffered
minor injuries.
</P>
<P>
   In the northern city of Schleswig, 58 neo-Nazis from across the
country were taken into custody Saturday after police found posters
with extreme-right slogans and baseball bats, police said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities in the eastern state of Sachsen-Anhalt also broke up
an attempted gathering Saturday evening to mark the anniversary
next week of the death of Hitler's deputy Rudolf Hess. They
arrested 16 people.
</P>
<P>
   More than 50 people have also been arrested in the eastern state
of Thuringia in the last three days in connection with
extreme-right crimes after police conducted a series of raids.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
