<HEADLINE> USS New Jersey to be moved to restoration site  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) - The USS New Jersey will be moved Tuesday
from the Beckett Street Terminal to the pier where it will be
converted into a floating museum.
</P>
<P>
   The Home Port Alliance, the nonprofit group that will restore
the ship, said the vessel will be towed to Pier 1 of the South
Jersey Port Corporation's Broadway Terminal at about 2 p.m.
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   There, the ship will undergo a $7.3 million restoration that is
expected to take about 14 months, said retired Capt. David
McGuigan, president of the Home Port Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   McGuigan said the restoration will include underwater hull
inspections and cleaning, hull and topside preservation and
painting, improvements to the teak deck, removal of hazardous
materials and the installation of various security, fire, flood and
safety systems. Some of the ship's interior also will be preserved.
</P>
<P>
   The Home Port Alliance plans to spend more than $20 million to
establish the USS New Jersey Memorial, including the ship
restoration, construction of a T-shaped pier and a shoreside
reception, museum and theater complex on the waterfront.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
