<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Car Bomb Explodes in Bogota  </HEADLINE>
By WILL WEISSERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- A car bomb exploded outside a police
station on the capital's outskirts Sunday, injuring a civilian,
amid rural clashes between troops and guerrillas that left at least
13 dead over the weekend, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The fighting has apparently escalated in the run-up to President
Clinton's planned visit to Colombia on Aug. 30.
</P>
<P>
   The bomb was intended for a military truck carrying soldiers as
it passed through a working class neighborhood in southern Bogota,
said Alfredo Salgado, assistant director of Colombia's national
police.
</P>
<P>
   But the explosives, packed into a Fiat sedan less than 20 yards
from the police station, exploded minutes after the truck passed
by, damaging several homes and buildings, and injuring one person,
Salgado said. The person was not identified.
</P>
<P>
   Police attributed the attack to the Revolutionary Armed Forces
of Colombia, or FARC, the country's largest guerrilla group.
</P>
<P>
   The explosion came amid a weekend of fighting in different parts
of Colombia that has left at least three soldiers and 10 guerrillas
dead, police said.
</P>
<P>
   A weekend battle that was still raging Sunday between about 500
FARC guerillas and government soldiers trying to reclaim a
rebel-controlled town has killed at least two soldiers and seven
rebels, said Gen. Heran Cadavid, head of the army's Sixth Brigade.
</P>
<P>
   The fighting broke out Saturday afternoon when soldiers moved
into Roncesvalles, a village 125 miles southwest of Bogota.
</P>
<P>
   FARC forces also laid siege to a hydroelectric plant in
Anchicacaya, 215 miles west of Bogota, on Saturday night, and seven
soldiers were wounded as they pursued the rebels, an army
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the country's second guerrilla group, the National
Liberation Army, or ELN, on Sunday was concluding a week-long
campaign of attacks to protest a $1.3 billion anti-drug trafficking
aid package for Colombia that Clinton signed into law last month.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will visit Colombia's port city of Cartagena to meet
with President Andres Pastrana and top anti-drug officials.
</P>
<P>
   The ELN vowed last Sunday to set up road blocks on major
highways and stage attacks for a week to protest the aid package.
</P>
<P>
   One soldier and two ELN guerrillas were killed in clashes
Saturday night at a pair of rebel road blocks near the northeastern
towns of Maceo and Segovia, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Police say ELN rebels also kidnapped dozens of people, destroyed
37 electric power stations, torched 69 cars and trucks and damaged
70 highways during their week of violence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-13-00 1733 </TRAILER>
