<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New York delegates call a posh hotel home  </HEADLINE>
By SHANNON McCAFFREY
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) - New York's delegates to the Democratic
Convention are staying in one of the fanciest hotels in town, but
they have one problem - no swimming pool.
</P>
<P>
   The Century Plaza pool is closed for construction.
</P>
<P>
   A late-night swim, however, will be one of the few things the
New Yorkers do without over the next four days of politicking and
partying.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel where the state's 294 delegates are staying is one of
Los Angeles' most expensive - the regular room rate is close to
$400 a night.
</P>
<P>
   Attending this year's convention is so pricey, in fact, that the
New York State Democratic Party has taken the unusual step of
offering financial aid for some cash-strapped delegates. Even so,
sticker shock kept at least one delegate home.
</P>
<P>
   ''It really was just too expensive for me to handle,'' said Ed
Collins, of Binghamton. Collins said he was less enthusiastic about
making the trip west because he supports Bill Bradley over Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ''But when you add the whole trip up, forget about it! I've got
two kids to think about,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While single rooms normally go for $385 the delegates are
receiving a discount rate of $215 a night. Guests can order Dom
Perignon from the room service menu for $175 or indulge in a
Beverly Hills shopping spree in nearby Rodeo Drive.
</P>
<P>
   State Democratic Party Chairwoman Judith Hope said seven
delegates had applied for and received financial assistance from
the party.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is an expensive convention for all of us,'' Hope
acknowledged. ''The plane ticket is expensive. Five days in L.A. is
expensive. I understand it's a sacrifice for people.''
</P>
<P>
   Not for New York's many labor union-affiliated delegates. The
unions were picking up the check for their members.
</P>
<P>
   And with the hectic schedule of corporate-sponsored receptions
and parties offering up free food and drink, New York delegates may
not need to fork over $50 for the Century Plaza's picnic lunch for
two that is stocked with brie and strawberries.
</P>
<P>
   The state's delegates appeared to be reveling in their
surroundings on the Avenue of the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's good to have a Senate candidate who is also the first
lady,'' said delegate Michael Welsh, of LeRoy.
</P>
<P>
   The party's top celebrity, Hillary Rodham Clinton, is staying
with the president right next door at the tony St. Regis Hotel. The
first lady will be popping over for a kickoff reception kick and
the delegation breakfast on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   And the delegates may not even need to worry about missing out
on a swim.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday afternoon a contingent of New Yorkers left the hotel
in t-shirts and shorts going in search of the beach.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-13-00 1815 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000813.0068 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Du-Maurier-Notebook  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   AYLMER, Quebec (AP) -- The sore back that forced Dottie Pepper to
withdraw midway through the second round of the U.S. Open will keep
her off the tour for another month.
</P>
<P>
   Pepper described the injury as ''functional overload'' caused by
''four years of doing too much.''
</P>
<P>
   ''This is an injury that has been coming on for quite a while,''
she said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Pepper, winless this year but still eighth on the LPGA money
list, said she is being treated by back specialist Tom Boers of
Columbus, Ga., whose other patients have included golfers Fred
Couples, Ernie Els and David Duval.
</P>
<P>
   Pepper said she is aiming to return to the LPGA Tour by the
Betsy King Classic in Kutztown, Pa., on Sept. 8, and she said there
is ''no doubt'' she will play in the United States vs. Europe
Solheim Cup, starting Oct. 6, in Scotland. She has already
qualified for the match-play event, in which she went 4-0 two years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   MAKING MONEY: Rosie Jones' winnings of $111,711 for finishing
second at the du Maurier Classic vaulted her from 12th to sixth in
the LPGA Tour's money list. Her season total is $533,875.
</P>
<P>
   That, though, was nothing like the bump tour rookie Diana
D'Alessio got in the rankings by cashing the biggest check of her
career. D'Alessio made $63,404 for finishing fourth and jumped from
116th to 62nd on the winnings list with $107,097.
</P>
<P>
   Meg Mallon credited D'Alessio with helping her win the du
Maurier.
</P>
<P>
   They played together on Saturday and Sunday, and Mallon said
D'Alessio made some impressive par saves.
</P>
<P>
   ''Talk about composure,'' Mallon said. ''She made so many putts
under pressure today -- today and yesterday. ... Sometimes when
another player is not playing well, it kind of distracts you. She
played great. I think she's going to be a very good player in years
to come for us.''
</P>
<P>
   D'Alessio lives in Flanders, N.J., and went to Furman
University.
</P>
<P>
   Mallon moved into the 10th spot on career LPGA Tour winnings
with the $180,000 she made Sunday, jumping past Laura Davies.
Mallon has made $5.17 million in 14 years on tour.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   VANDALISM: Lorie Kane fans carved ''Go Canada'' and ''I am
Kane-adian'' into the first green at the Royal Ottawa Golf Club
sometime Saturday. Though patched up by grounds crews before
Saturday's round, the words were faintly visible Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-13-00 1822 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000813.0069 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
