<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> School board members in impoverished Camden run up travel, food expenses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) - As they were asking the state to increase
aid, school board members in this impoverished city were spending
lavishly on themselves for travel and food, according to a
published report.
</P>
<P>
   Board members spent nearly $100,000 on expenses in the 1999-2000
school year - almost twice what was budgeted, according to The
Philadelphia Inquirer, which examined the board's expenses and
purchase orders.
</P>
<P>
   In the fiscal year that ended June 30, the nine-member board
spent $54,000 on travel, including airfare and hotels, $13,642 on
conference registration fees and $7,897 on food, the newspaper
reported. They also spent $588 on flowers and donations and $753 on
cab fares.
</P>
<P>
   For three consecutive years, the board overspent its $50,000
expense budget. Money was transferred from other accounts,
including salaries and facilities, to cover the costs, the paper
reported.
</P>
<P>
   Camden is southern New Jersey's largest district, with 19,000
students. The board's $50,000 expense allotment is considerably
more than what other neighboring boards allow.
</P>
<P>
   Cherry Hill, which has 11,000 students, budgets $5,000 per year
for board expenses, and Willingboro, with 5,600 pupils, allows
$3,400, the newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia, which has 209,000 students, budgets $100,000 per
year for board expenses.
</P>
<P>
   The district spent $7,600 in January for the board and top
administrators to attend a two-day retreat in Princeton. Board
members said they chose a location away from Camden to avoid
distractions.
</P>
<P>
   Board members spent up to $122 per day for meals while on
business trips and also charged personal expenses to the district,
the newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
   During a trip to Atlanta, board member Rosemary J. Jackson
ordered five movies and room service totaling nearly $300, and made
$112 worth of phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, who traveled more than any other board member, defended
her trips, saying she has made contacts around the country and used
some of what she's learned to sponsor a curriculum fair and
education symposium.
</P>
<P>
   She also defended her spending, saying the phone calls were
necessary because of her work as a consultant, and the only chance
she gets to watch movies is when she's away.
</P>
<P>
   State regulations bar school board members from being paid for
their services.
</P>
<P>
   ''In terms of what I give up, in hours, work and commitment ...
I don't think there's a comparison, she told the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Board members also spent lavishly on catered meals during board
meetings, paying the soul-food restaurant Corinne's Place $500 per
month. The board instructed the restaurant to provide meals for 30
people, even though there are only nine board members. Containers
for carryout were provided.
</P>
<P>
   The state Department of Education's Compliance Investigation
Office is examining the spending and questioning board members, the
newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
   Board President Philip E. Freeman Sr. acknowledged that ''there
are no checks and balances'' and said he welcomes the state review.
</P>
<P>
   Camden has a $247 million school district budget and has said it
needs $27 million more in state aid this year.
</P>
<P>
   Spending in the district has caught the attention of the state
in previous years. Former board president Elaine Bey was jailed in
1998 for embezzling more than $24,000 and former Mayor Arnold
Webster admitted illegally paying himself $20,000 from school board
funds after becoming mayor.
</P>
<P>
   State officials said any findings from their current probe that
warrant criminal investigation will be given to state prosecutors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-13-00 1844 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000813.0073 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> All Not Right With Unbeaten Ravens  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID GINSBURG
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE (AP) -- Brian Billick clenched his teeth as he spoke
about the Baltimore Ravens' offensive performance against the New
York Jets.
</P>
<P>
   ''We moved the ball around pretty good, but the focus, the
attention to detail, the execution, just wasn't there,'' he said.
''Our task is clearly in front of us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ravens' lone touchdown in Saturday night's 10-0 victory came
on Chris McAlister's 33-yard interception return. The first team
offense produced only three points, and quarterback Tony Banks
irritated Billick by letting the clock expire in the first half
with the Ravens at the New York 11-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hopefully we can learn a lesson and not have that catch us in
the regular season,'' Billick said.
</P>
<P>
   At least Banks made it out of the game healthy, and that is no
small feat. The Jets lost two quarterbacks to injury -- Vinny
Testaverde hyperextended his left big toe and Chad Pennington left
with a sprained left knee.
</P>
<P>
   ''We got out of Dodge, so to speak, with some bumps and bruises
and pulls, so you've got to feel fortunate,'' Billick said.
</P>
<P>
   Starting right guard Mike Flynn sprained his right foot and is
doubtful for the Ravens' next game, Friday night on the road
against Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mike needs every snap he can get, so that's unfortunate,''
Billick said.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore has won 10 straight preseason games, but Billick
expected more from an offense that during the offseason added
several weapons, including tight ends Shannon Sharpe and Ben Coates
and rookie wide receiver Travis Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   The Ravens had decent field position in the first half against
the Jets, and Priest Holmes had 78 yards rushing on only 12
carries. But the offense never got into the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   ''We can't be a club like we were last year, where we were so
comfortable that our defense is going to give us great field
position every time,'' Banks said. ''We've got to hold up our end
of the bargain.''
</P>
<P>
   The defense has certainly done its part, forcing seven turnovers
in two weeks, including two interceptions and a fumble recovery
against the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've been working on getting turnovers all training camp, and
it's paying off,'' defensive coordinator Marvin Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   The Ravens play their final two preseason games on the road
before opening the regular season at Pittsburgh. They then host
Jacksonville, travel to Miami and face Cincinnati at home before
beginning a string of three straight road games.
</P>
<P>
   ''The journey begins for us now,'' Billick said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-13-00 1844 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000813.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peirsol: Krayzelburg is Beatable  </HEADLINE>
By BETH HARRIS
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Aaron Peirsol doesn't agree with the
mentality that everyone is swimming for second when backstroke
world record-holder Lenny Krayzelburg is in the pool.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everyone keeps mentioning that Lenny is unbeatable,'' Peirsol
said. ''Everyone thinks first is out of reach.''
</P>
<P>
   Peirsol, 17, knows firsthand that isn't true.
</P>
<P>
   Swimming in Krayzelburg's home pool, Peirsol beat the Ukraine
native at 200 meters last month at a Los Angeles meet. It was
Krayzelburg's first loss in that event in two years.
</P>
<P>
   ''The young guys are able to drop times so fast,'' Krayzelburg
said. ''He brings out the best in me.''
</P>
<P>
   Krayzelburg, 24, and Peirsol, of Irvine, Calif., resume their
burgeoning rivalry in the 200 backstroke final at the U.S. Olympic
trials Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   It's one of four finals on the sixth night six of the eight-day
trials. The others are the women's 200 breaststroke and 100
freestyle, and the men's 200 individual medley.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Peirsol became the third-fastest man ever
behind Krayzelburg and 1992 Olympic champion Martin Zubero of
Spain. In 1999, he was the youngest man ever to break two minutes
in the 200 back.
</P>
<P>
   Krayzelburg and Peirsol were two seconds ahead of the field
after Sunday's prelims, and the only ones under 2 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Krayzelburg, the favorite for two backstroke golds in Sydney,
welcomes the competition.
</P>
<P>
   ''For the last two years I've been swimming by myself,'' he
said. ''If someone is with you, you have to use a lot more strategy
in your race. It's going to be better for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Krayzelburg owns the world and American records of 1 minute,
55.87 seconds in the 200. He'll be looking to lower his world mark
Monday, a feat he failed to achieve in the 100 back final Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''A lot of people were talking about it. I was talking about
it,'' he said. ''I really thought I was going to break that
record.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that he's on the Olympic team in the 100 back, Krayzelburg
isn't putting as much pressure on himself.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to see fast times, it's possible we could see a
world record,'' he said. ''I wouldn't be surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   Krayzelburg sees his biggest Olympic competition coming from
Peirsol in the 200 back and Neil Walker, of Austin, Texas, in the
100 back.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is good preparation here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jenny Thompson and Dara Torres resume their battle in the 100
freestyle, where Thompson holds the American record -- a mark she
lowered last month at a meet in Los Angeles. Both already are on
the Olympic team in individual events.
</P>
<P>
   Amy Van Dyken, a four-time gold medalist in the Atlanta Games,
swims her first event of the trials Monday in the 100 free. She'll
also go in Tuesday's 50 free preliminaries.
</P>
<P>
   ''The 50 is obviously my favorite. It's my baby,'' said Van
Dyken, who won the 50 gold in Atlanta. ''The 100 is kind of the
icing on the cake for me, kind of get the jitters out before the
50.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Dyken, 27, underwent shoulder surgery in June 1998 and then
again last January, after which she wasn't able to raise her right
shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ''All I had really wanted to do was to make it to trials and now
I'm hoping to make the Olympic team. How weird is that?'' she said.
''It's been a long road, but it's been a lot of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   In the men's 200 IM, Tom Wilkens faces Tom Dolan again. Wilkens
was on world-record pace in the 400 IM at 300 meters Tuesday when
Dolan and Erik Vendt overtook him to earn Olympic berths.
</P>
<P>
   Kristy Kowal, 16-year-old Megan Quann and Amanda Beard, silver
medalist in Atlanta, will fight for two available spots in the 200
breaststroke. Beard is down to her last chance to make the team
after failing in the 100 breast, where she also won silver in
Atlanta.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-13-00 1845 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000813.0075 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swimmer Calls Krayzelburg 'Beatable'  </HEADLINE>
By BETH HARRIS
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Aaron Peirsol doesn't agree with the
mentality that everyone is swimming for second when backstroke
world record-holder Lenny Krayzelburg is in the pool.
