<DOCNO> APW20000813.0076 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 18:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swimmer Van Dyken Healing Quickly  </HEADLINE>
By PAUL NEWBERRY
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Amy Van Dyken never thought she'd feel this
good.
</P>
<P>
   The winner of four gold medals in Atlanta -- the most by an
American woman at one Olympics -- Van Dyken was preparing to watch
the Sydney Games on television after two shoulder surgeries the
past two years.
</P>
<P>
   But she has made a remarkable recovery since her latest one in
January, posting the fifth-fastest time Sunday in preliminaries for
the 100-meter freestyle at the U.S. Olympic trials.
</P>
<P>
   ''That was really good,'' said Van Dyken, whose time of 55.55
seconds put her less than a second behind top qualifier Dara
Torres. ''I looked around (in her heat) and there wasn't anybody,
so I kind of backed off a little bit. It was a lot of fun and it
was a good race.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Dyken, 27, underwent shoulder surgery June 1998 and needed
another operation at the beginning of this year. She only resumed
training in March.
</P>
<P>
   ''Never felt better,'' she said. ''Everything's going better
than I thought it would. I wasn't expecting a lot coming here. To
be seeded fifth after the morning and to have a time like that --
things are perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Dyken didn't feel things were so perfect after surgery.
Heck, she wasn't even able to lift her right arm -- quite a handicap
for a swimmer.
</P>
<P>
   ''All I had really wanted to do was to make it to the trials,''
she said. ''Now, I'm hoping to make the Olympic team. How weird is
that? It's been a long road, but it's been a lot of fun and I've
learned a lot about myself as a person and as a swimmer.''
</P>
<P>
   The 33-year-old Torres, in another remarkable performance by
someone who retired from the sport for seven years, led the prelims
at 54.62. She was followed by Jenny Thompson (54.72), who edged
Torres in a thrilling 100 butterfly Thursday, giving them both a
spot on the Olympic team.
</P>
<P>
   Torres was bothered by cramps Friday in the 200 freestyle,
forcing her to drop out after the preliminaries. She didn't feel
much better when she arrived at the Indiana University Natatorium
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I told Richard (Quick, her coach), 'I feel like crap,''' she
said. ''He asked me to explain and I said, 'C-R-A-P.'''
</P>
<P>
   Torres felt better after warming up. When the race ended, she
was pleased to see so many of her contemporaries reaching the
semifinals, including Angel Martino, who is 10 days younger and the
mother of a 3-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   ''It means we're going to have a great relay,'' Torres said.
''It's great to have the older women dominating the sprint
events.''
</P>
<P>
   Torres and Thompson were the only women to eclipse 55 seconds in
the morning.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wanted to have a comfortable swim and I felt like I did
that,'' Thompson said. ''You don't win the race in the prelims and
no one is looking to do that. I'm just planning to have the best of
the three (races) in the finals.''
</P>
<P>
   The 27-year-old, who has won five gold medals and a silver at
the Olympics, was relieved to clinch a spot on the team so early in
the trials. Four years ago, she shockingly failed to qualify in any
of her individual events and had to settle for a spot on the relay
teams.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't have that stress,'' she said, ''so I'm much more
comfortable taking it easy in the prelims.''
</P>
<P>
   Likewise for Torres, who feels she is just entering her prime
after retiring from swimming to dabble in modeling and television
work.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is the way I should have been swimming when I was
younger,'' she said. ''Every one thinks it a miracle I'm swimming
so much faster now. But this is what I had in me when I was
younger. It just didn't work out.''
</P>
<P>
   In other morning prelims, Lenny Krayzelburg breezed into the
semis of the 200 backstroke with a leading time of 1:58.79.
Seventeen-year-old Aaron Peirsol of Irvine, Calif., was second at
1:58.90 -- no one else cracked 2 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Krayzelburg already made the team in the 100 backstroke.
</P>
<P>
   Kristy Kowal of Athens, Ga., bouncing back from the
disappointment of finishing third in the 100 breaststroke,
dominated qualifying in the 200 breast at 2:26.32, while
16-year-old Megan Quann of Puyallup, Wash., was next at 2:28.12.
The teen-ager won the 100 breast.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Wilkens of Palo Alto, Calif., began a busy day by pacing the
200 individual medley at 2:02.96. In the evening, he was to swim
both the semifinals of the IM as well as the 200 breaststroke
final.
</P>
<P>
   The other two finals were women's 200 butterfly and men's 100
freestyle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-13-00 1855 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000813.0077 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Buick Open Notebook  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND BLANC, Mich. (AP) -- Woody Austin got himself some job
security this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't quite enough to send him home with a smile, though.
</P>
<P>
   Austin led the Buick Open by two shots after two rounds, but had
rounds of 73 and 70 on the weekend to tie for fourth, five shots
behind winner Rocco Mediate.
</P>
<P>
   That earned him $118,800, enough to secure a spot in the top 125
on the PGA Tour money list and a playing card for the 2001 season.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm ecstatic about the money,'' Austin said Sunday. ''I really
wanted to get things done by Reno (Aug. 21-27), because I didn't
want to play in the two events in Canada after that. Now I don't
have to worry about it. I can take some vacation and relax.''
</P>
<P>
   Austin is in the tour's bottom 20 in putting.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've talked to guys like Brad Faxon and Ben Crenshaw, and I've
gotten better on short putts, but I'm still like 175th,'' he said.
''It's all about confidence. If you don't have that, you will never
get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   Austin, whose only career win came at the 1995 Buick Open, was
disgusted by his play on the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ''I birdied the first two holes Saturday, and if I could have
just played even-par golf from there on in, then shot the same
score today, I would have been right there,'' Austin said. ''And
that's not making any big putts -- that's just keeping bogeys off
the card and making the tap ins. It's great to play this well - but
I'm really disappointed that I didn't do more.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   UP AND DOWN ROUND: Carl Paulson tied for sixth thanks to two
great runs of birdies Sunday. First, after bogeying the 5th, he
birdied Nos. 6, 7 and 8. After a bogey on No. 9 and routine pars on
10 and 11, he birdied the next three holes, parred the tough 15th
and birdied 16th. In all, he had eight birdies, two bogeys and only
eight pars.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   ENDANGERED SPECIES: Once again, the 15th hole was the hardest
on the course, with Mediate, Tiger Woods and Hal Sutton among those
who dropped a shot there Sunday. Dudley Hart, though, managed an
eagle from the fairway, the first on 15 in the history of the
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   LEGENDARY PAIRING: Woods was happy to hear the solution for
his pairing at the PGA Championship this week at Valhalla.
Normally, the winners of the three majors play together in the
first two rounds, but Woods made that impossible by winning both
the U.S. and British Opens.
</P>
<P>
   Another solution would have been to add last year's PGA
champion, but of course, Woods won that as well.
</P>
<P>
   So the PGA decided to pair Woods and Masters champ Vijay Singh
with Jack Nicklaus. Nicklaus, 60, is playing his last full year of
majors, and is also Valhalla's designer.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was wondering what they were going to do with our group,''
Woods said Sunday. ''That sounds like it is going to be a lot of
fun to play.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   GETTING CLOSER THE SECOND TIME: Sunday's last-group duel was
hardly the first head-to-head matchup between Mediate and Chris
Perry. The pair played in the Sweet 16 round of the Western Amateur
in 1984. As he did Sunday, Mediate came out on top, but not by only
one shot.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was playing some kid from Pennsylvania who used this tiny
putter and whose dad walked every hole with him,'' Perry said. ''I
had never heard of him, and he birdied everything and beat me 6 and
5. I told him that after he did it again today, he should at least
give me the hubcaps off his new Buick.''
</P>
<P>
   Mediate said that the outcome was a fluke.
</P>
<P>
   ''Chris was a great amateur and won dozens of tournaments, and I
won two,'' he said. ''If I beat him more than 1-up, he must have
really had a bad day.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Divots: Neal Lancaster won the award for consistency, shooting
1-under 71s in all four rounds. ... Loren Roberts tied for 16th at
12 under, and moved past Notah Begay for the last automatic spot on
the American Presidents Cup team. The team is selected on the basis
of money won through the PGA Championship. ... Brett Quigley
birdied all four par-5s on Sunday, making him the only player to do
that all weekend. Quigley also added an eagle on the par-4 14th for
a season-low round of 64.
</P>
</TEXT>
