<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ehud Barak Bypasses Parliament  </HEADLINE>
By EMMA BLIJDENSTEIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak reappointed
two dovish ministers to his government Sunday, bypassing parliament
and eliciting sharp criticism from hard-line opposition parties.
</P>
<P>
   Barak is trying hard to show that it's government as usual, even
though three parties have bolted his coalition over his
far-reaching peace offers to the Palestinians and he is governing
with just 42 legislators out of 120 in the parliament, or Knesset.
By naming new ''acting ministers,'' Barak is avoiding the Knesset
approval for Cabinet appointments required by law.
</P>
<P>
   Meretz party leader Yossi Sarid said he and Barak agreed that he
would return as education minister, a post he left in June.
</P>
<P>
   Former Industry and Trade Minister Ran Cohen, also of Meretz,
said he too would return to his post as an acting minister. He had
left his position at the same time as Sarid.
</P>
<P>
   Barak's office would not comment. Meretz officials said a formal
announcement was likely on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The two were squeezed out of the Cabinet in a bid to appease the
religious Shas party, a key-player in the peace process. Shas and
the secular Meretz party had been locked in a bitter dispute over
control of religious schools.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Barak had felt he needed Shas in government to
secure its hawkish constituency's support for far-reaching peace
moves, while he knew he could count on Meretz support whether or
not they held Cabinet posts.
</P>
<P>
   Shas then left government a month later over proposals Barak was
planning to make at the Camp David peace summit, including
extending limited sovereignty to the Palestinians in parts of
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Meretz now intends to play an active part in peace negotiations,
Sarid told Israeli television on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The two Meretz politicians were the latest ''acting ministers''
named by Barak to fill in his government. On Sunday, Labor party
secretary-general Raanan Cohen took his post as acting labor
minister, a post vacated by Shas leader Eli Ishai.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Barak made Shlomo Ben-Ami acting foreign minister,
and Roni Milo of the Center Party is expected to be named acting
health minister Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition lawmakers claimed the ''acting minister''
appointments might be illegal because they bypass Knesset review.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is an appointment that seems ... in defiance of the Basic
Law of the Government,'' Likud-party lawmaker Limor Livnat said on
Israeli television. She asked the Supreme Court to force Barak to
bring the appointments to the Knesset for approval.
</P>
<P>
   The prime minister is safe from parliamentary efforts to topple
him while the Knesset is in recess -- until October. After that, he
may be able to cobble together a minority government that, together
with outside support from Arab parties, would keep him in power
long enough to wrap up a peace deal with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   A senior Barak aide has said Barak aims to stay in power long
enough to complete a peace deal. While Camp David failed to produce
an agreement, negotiators on both sides said breakthroughs at the
summit made a permanent status agreement much likelier.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Jewish settlers agreed Sunday to remove illegal
mobile homes they had put up on West Bank hilltops in a bid to
expand their settlements, an Israeli Defense Ministry official
said.
</P>
<P>
   The settlers had put up seven caravans and two large containers
at locations nar the Nof Kana and Bruchim settlements in the
northern West Bank. The ministry official said the army would
remove the homes if the settlers failed to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, settlers agreed with Barak to stop illegal settlement
building while he pursued peace talks. But the settlers declared
the deal void last month because of Barak's offers to the
Palestinians at Camp David.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
