<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NFL Camps Roundup  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Carolina Panthers kicker John Kasay is expected to
miss the
entire season after fracturing his left kneecap during a morning
workout Sunday.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The bone in the left-footed kicker's knee was broken nearly in
half, coach George Seifert said. Kasay, a Pro Bowl selection in
1996, was taken from training camp at Wofford College in
Spartanburg, S.C. to Charlotte, N.C., for surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Kasay, the team's leading scorer every year since they joined
the NFL, was practicing with the team for just the second time
since returning from surgery to repair a torn anterior cruciate
ligament in the same knee. That injury happened in a December game,
and Seifert wasn't sure if the two injuries are related.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Kasay was attempting a 30-yard field goal when, as
his foot connected with the ball, he screamed: ''Oh no! No!
Trainer! Trainer!'' The ball squirted away off to the left.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was hard for me to see that much,'' said punter Ken Walter,
who holds for field goals. ''I was concentrating on the hold, but I
kind of felt something that wasn't normal. He didn't get a good
foot on the ball. Next thing you know, I hear him yelling and
squirming around on the ground.''
Jets:
</P>
<P>
   Vinny Testaverde's preseason is over after the quarterback was
hurt in the second quarter of Saturday night's 10-0 exhibition loss
at Baltimore. The injury is to the same foot on which he tore his
Achilles' tendon in the 1999 opener, costing him the rest of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   But coach Al Groh made it clear Sunday that Testaverde's toe is
a short-term problem.
</P>
<P>
   ''It will probably be a week before he is really up to going
hard,'' Groh said. ''That is what I am going to start this week
with and when we get to the next week, see how it is.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's out for Friday, that's probably the way things will go.
This is only Sunday, we just had the injury last night, so it is
premature to have an idea what the course of his week will be
like.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the regular season-opener against Green Bay on Sept. 3,
Groh is confidently hopeful regarding Testaverde's availability.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's too early to speculate on that now, but with the
indications now and with aggressive treatment, he should be ready.
We'll see how he throws with it when we get him back,'' Groh said.
Browns:
</P>
<P>
   Coach Chris Palmer said Sunday he will likely wait until other
NFL teams reduce their rosters to find a backup for quarterback Tim
Couch in the wake of Ty Detmer's season-ending injury.
</P>
<P>
   Detmer was lost for the season Saturday night when he ruptured
an Achilles' tendon during Cleveland's 19-6 loss to the Chicago
Bears.
</P>
<P>
   Detmer, a nine-year veteran, was changing directions while
scrambling out of the pocket in the second quarter when he went
down. He will undergo surgery on Monday and will need 6-to-8 months
of rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer said it was too early to determine whether the injury to
the 32-year-old Detmer was career threatening.
Steelers:
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh signed former Michigan State running back Lloyd
Clemons, an undrafted free agent who was cut by the Baltimore
Ravens.
</P>
<P>
   Clemons was signed Sunday after backup running back Chris
Fuamatu-Ma'afala cracked two ribs in Thursday's preseason game
against Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Clemons led Michigan State with 959 yards last season.
Bears:
</P>
<P>
   Although Jaret Holmes and Paul Edinger are both 3-for-3 in field
goal attempts during the preseason, coach Dick Jauron said the team
would not hesitate to bring in another veteran kicker as they have
already done with Jeff Jaeger and Michael Husted.
</P>
<P>
   Holmes hit from 54 and 48 yards in Saturday night's preseason
victory over Cleveland, and Paul Edinger was good on two
34-yarders.
</P>
<P>
   ''They have both kicked well enough in games to show they belong
in the league and there is a lot of pressure on them from the
press, from us and from themselves,'' Jauron said.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis Enis gained 37 yards on 10 carries Saturday night, a
marked improvement from his five-carry, 8-yard performance the
previous week.
</P>
</TEXT>
