<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 19:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Company calls new proposal comprehensive, unions say it sets talks back </HEADLINE>
By KALPANA SRINIVASAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) - Thousands of technicians and operators for
Verizon Communications entered their second week on strike Sunday,
leaving consumers in the Northeast and Mid-Atlantic states saddled
with more delays in telephone repairs and installations.
</P>
<P>
   At the bargaining table, the unions rebuffed the latest company
proposal delivered to negotiators shortly after midnight Saturday.
Key stumbling blocks such as mandatory overtime and the shifting of
workloads within the company's expanded territory remain largely
unaddressed, the unions said, or in some cases matters have been
made worse.
</P>
<P>
   ''Verizon had better put its energies into serious collective
bargaining if it wants to end this strike any time soon,'' warned
Morton Bahr, president of the Communications Workers of America -
the larger of the two unions bargaining.
</P>
<P>
   Early Sunday, the company offered what it called a ''revised
comprehensive offer'' to CWA and the International Brotherhood of
Electrical Workers to respond to problems the union had found with
earlier company offers.
</P>
<P>
   ''We now believe we have gone a good distance down that road,''
Verizon spokesman Eric Rabe said. ''We continue to believe we've
got the right package here.''
</P>
<P>
   But union officials said the proposal did not address key
issues, such as shifting of work by Verizon from the former Bell
Atlantic territory to GTE's region. Verizon is the product of a
summer marriage between those two companies.
</P>
<P>
   CWA bargainers said the only company proposal addressing
overtime - related to the definition of a ''reasonable excuse'' for
turning down forced overtime - would weaken existing workers'
rights.
</P>
<P>
   The unions also asserted that the company is now seeking
concessions on the matter of job stress for employees in call
centers. According to CWA, Verizon wants to limit to 1.5 percent
the number of workers that can transfer each month. Union officials
argue that this traps customer service representatives and
consultants in high-pressure jobs without opportunities for
movement.
</P>
<P>
   Rabe said he was disappointed at the tone of the comments and
said again that the company has tried to sweeten the pot for its
workers in recent negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, 4,800 Puerto Rican telephone workers - who have been
bargaining for several months with the former GTE, now Verizon -
plan informational pickets and ''collective actions'' to show their
solidarity with the striking employees in the East. Those
employees, members of the Independent Union of Telephone Workers
are now working without a contract.
</P>
<P>
   More than a week has passed since contracts expired for 87,000
Verizon workers in the East. The company's 30,000 managers have
jumped in to tackle a daily running total of 90,000 repair orders,
a problem exacerbated because of inclement weather in parts of the
Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the strike dragging into a second week, the company says
it will not call in federal mediators so long as the parties make
some progress in their talks.
</P>
<P>
   On hurdles that remain, the unions say the company's policy of
requiring overtime severely disrupts workers' family lives,
particularly employees who are single parents. The unions also fear
the addition of GTE territory to Bell Atlantic's Northeast and
Middle Atlantic base will make it possible for the company to shift
work to areas where labor is cheaper.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon says stringent hiring standards and a tight labor market
make it difficult to add new workers. Flexibility in vacation
policies that let union workers take days off with minimal notice
also means the company needs to have others fill in, Rabe said.
</P>
<P>
   He also insisted that union workers have significant job
security guarantees already and the company is constantly adding
positions - increasing its union-represented work force by 3,000
this year alone.
</P>
<P>
   The strike affects Delaware, Maine, Maryland, Massachusetts, New
Hampshire, New Jersey, New York, Pennsylvania, Rhode Island,
Vermont, Virginia, West Virginia and Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Verizon Communications: http://www.verizon.com
</P>
<P>
   Communications Workers of America: http://www.cwa-union.org
</P>
<P>
   International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers:
http://www.ibew.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
