<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Newspaper: Lame fire code enforcement in four NJ counties  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HACKENSACK, N.J. (AP) - Nearly 12 percent of buildings in a
survey of four northern New Jersey counties weren't inspected last
year for state fire code violations, according to a published
report.
</P>
<P>
   Officials have said New Jersey has some of the most stringent
regulations to protect the public from fires. They were put into
effect 15 years ago after a series of deadly boarding home fires.
</P>
<P>
   But among 93 communities in Bergen, Passaic, Morris and Hudson
counties surveyed by The Record of Hackensack, about 12 percent of
600 buildings considered ''life hazard uses'' were not inspected.
</P>
<P>
   Life hazard uses are places where a fire would be particularly
catastrophic, such as schools, nursing homes, shopping malls, movie
theaters or buildings that are prone to fire because combustible
material is stored or used on the premises.
</P>
<P>
   The state's Uniform Fire Code says those buildings considered
life hazard uses must be inspected at least once a year by a
certified official and that records of those inspections should be
kept on file.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper then projected its findings over the four counties
to conclude that between 1,143 and 1,214 buildings were not
inspected in 1999. The report also concluded that between 8,071 and
8,570 buildings were inspected in that year. The result had a
margin of error of 3.3 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper also reported that between 668 and 709 life hazard
use buildings have no record of inspection.
</P>
<P>
   The city of Clifton had the worst record for doing inspections
on time, the newspaper reported. It missed 19 of the 33 life hazard
uses in a sample of buildings the newspaper collected. Eight of
those buildings had not been inspected in five years, according to
the report.
</P>
<P>
   And in Lyndhurst, officials didn't even keep records of fire
inspections. That prompted the state Division of Fire Safety to
strip Michael Antonicelli of his responsibility as fire official
last summer.
</P>
<P>
   ''The enforcement of fire prevention - the inspection part of it
- is something that has to get emphasized to the locals,'' William
H. Cane, director of the New Jersey Division of Fire Safety, told
The Record.
</P>
<P>
   Cane said he had not realized that many towns were violating New
Jersey's fire inspection requirements.
</P>
<P>
   But even Cane's agency had some trouble keeping up with its
inspections, failing for two years to inspect the Meadowlands
Sports Complex, home to the Giants football team in East
Rutherford, the newspaper said. Inspectors from May through July
found 1,301 fire violations in the stadium. It had last been
inspected in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Local fire officials told the newspaper they could not inspect
all life hazard use buildings on time because of their other
duties, which include inspecting homes and small businesses and
teaching communities about fire safety.
</P>
<P>
   ''We try to do it all, and, sure, we fall behind on life hazard
uses,'' said Clifton Fire Chief John E. Dubravsky. ''I think more
emphasis should be put on residential fire safety.''
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper's investigation was prompted by a Jan. 19
dormitory fire at Seton Hall University that killed three students.
In the days after the fire, South Orange officials acknowledged
that they did not inspect the campus in 1999 and kept unclear
records of earlier inspections.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-13-00 1924 </TRAILER>
