<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barricaded man who shot three officers wanted to be a cop  </HEADLINE>
By VERENA DOBNIK
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - The deranged man who wounded four police
officers from two Brooklyn houses was once a jail guard who aspired
to become an officer, authorities said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   After Saturday's siege that ended in the death of the gunman,
Arthur Alalouf, police found an arsenal in his basement, along with
a dead dog and cat and ''dozens and dozens of samurai swords, Bowie
knives, and hundreds of rounds of ammunition,'' said police Chief
of Detectives William Allee Jr.
</P>
<P>
   The 47-year-old former correction officer was dressed in a
camouflage shirt and armed with a survival knife when he died
trying to escape at the end of the six-hour siege.
</P>
<P>
   A day earlier, Alalouf warned his parents ''that he would shoot
the police,'' Mayor Rudolph Giuliani quoted his parents as telling
officers at the 61st Precinct in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   The elderly couple had gone there to report that their son
purchased weapons Friday and brought them to the home they shared
in the Gravesend section of Brooklyn. They also told police he had
asked his family to leave, or he would burn down the house, said
police Sgt. Janet Velez.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday at about 1:45 p.m., as police approached the house,
he opened fire with a shotgun from a back window.
</P>
<P>
   Officer Gregory John was hit, suffering a shoulder wound.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani later displayed the officer's Kevlar vest, which had at
least eight holes where the buckshot had torn into the chest area.
</P>
<P>
   ''Thank God for the vest,'' Giuliani said. Officer John actually
was wearing two vests - his personal vest beneath his uniform, and
a heavier ESU vest on top.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of police officers descended upon the area and
evacuated neighbors from nearby houses.
</P>
<P>
   At some point after the shootout from his home at 16 Parkway
Court, Alalouf made a dash through the backyard and across a fence
to a nearby home, Giuliani said.
</P>
<P>
   Not knowing he had fled, police entered the first house with
infrared robotic cameras and tried to distract the gunman with
flash and stun grenades.
</P>
<P>
   Alalouf remained hidden in the second house until about 8 p.m.,
when police approached the front door and he opened fire.
</P>
<P>
   Officer James McGrath, 33, suffered a graze wound to the face,
and Officer Jose Guerra, 34, was struck in the face and leg, said
Officer Louis Cruz, a police spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect fled out the back window, where the fourth officer,
Jose Ocasio, 43, was shot once in the left calf, Cruz said.
</P>
<P>
   Police fired back and Alalouf was fatally wounded. He was
pronounced dead at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   In the basement of his home, police found a cache of firearms
that included five rifles, two other Mini-14 assault rifles,
holsters, survival equipment and four pistols - two licensed for
target shooting and two unregistered.
</P>
<P>
   The dog and cat were sealed in a box, and appeared to be dead
about a month, Allee said. It was unclear how they died. Also found
in the house were several live dogs.
</P>
<P>
   The Mossberg 12-guage shotgun used to wound the officers, as
well as one of the Mini-14s and the hundreds of rounds of
ammunition, were purchased Friday at a gun shop on New Utrecht
Avenue in Brooklyn, said Allee, the chief of detectives.
</P>
<P>
   The weapons were obtained legally, and Alalouf had a month to
register them. He paid for them with his father's credit card.
</P>
<P>
   John, the 32-year-old Emergency Service Unit officer with 10
years on the job, was in stable condition Saturday at Kings County
Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   McGrath and Guerra, also members of the Emergency Service Unit,
also were being treated at Kings County Hospital. Three other
officers suffered minor injuries that were not gunshot-related,
including scratches.
</P>
<P>
   Guerra, who suffered eye damage and had bullet fragments lodged
in his esophagus, was in serious condition. Ocasio was conscious
''and seems to be doing well,'' Giuliani said.
</P>
<P>
   McGrath reportedly was released.
</P>
<P>
   While the three hospitalized officers were ''in a great deal of
pain,'' Giuliani said, he was relieved that none had been wounded
by ''friendly fire.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor described Alalouf as ''obviously seriously deranged.''
</P>
<P>
   Authorities could not immediately obtain his employment record,
but Giuliani said he worked as a New York correction officer from
1982 to 1984; he was fired after complaints against him the mayor
said were ''unsubstantiated.''
</P>
<P>
   At some point after that, ''he made an attempt to become a
police officer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
