<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil Prepares Land Massacre Trial  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL ASTOR
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- Police blocked roads and set up
checkpoints across an Amazon city before Monday's trials of
suspects in one of the bloodiest land disputes in Brazilian
history.
</P>
<P>
   Some 10,000 people were expected attend the trial of the 13
Rondonia state police and two squatters charged in a 1995 clash
that left 10 farm workers and two police officers dead.
</P>
<P>
   Officers stopped and searched those entering Porto Velho, 2,000
miles northwest of Rio de Janeiro, along the city's only access
road. Scythes, machetes and other farm tools were being confiscated
to avoid violence, police chief Severino Moreira said by telephone.
</P>
<P>
   Police shut down roads adjacent to the courthouse and set up
tents and a large-screen television so landless rural workers could
watch the trials.
</P>
<P>
   The massacre occurred Aug. 9, 1995, when state police tried to
evict 500 squatters from the Santa Elina ranch in Corumbiara, a
small town 500 miles south of Porto Velho.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors claim some 300 police encircled the camp around 2:00
a.m., tossed in tear gas and stun grenades and invaded the
settlement with guns blazing.
</P>
<P>
   Autopsy reports later showed that of the 10 squatters killed,
seven were shot point blank in the face, neck, chest and back. One
victim, Ercilio Oliveira de Campos, was shot 19 times. Another, who
was not identified, was shot 12 times in the face.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the police were expected to argue they were met with
gunfire as they arrived to carry out an eviction order. Squatters
had asked the government to carve out a small plot for them, but
local ranchers insisted on expelling them.
</P>
<P>
   The accused police and squatters will be tried separately. If
convicted, they could face hefty prison terms, although under
Brazilian law no one may serve more than 30 years at a single
stretch.
</P>
<P>
   The case has taken five years to get to trial due to the complex
nature of the country's justice system. Some say the politically
explosive nature of the case has also dragged the matter out.
</P>
<P>
   Unequal land distribution is at the root of rural violence in
Brazil, where 90 percent of the land belongs to 20 percent of the
people, and the poorest 40 percent own just 1 percent of the land.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past decade more than 1,000 people have lost their
lives in land disputes in Brazil, according to the Land Pastoral, a
Catholic group that advocates land reform.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-13-00 2018 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000813.0096 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore's Daughters Work Convention  </HEADLINE>
By LAURAN NEERGAARD
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Politics always was a family affair to Al
Gore, groomed by his parents for Washington life. Now a third
generation of Gores takes up the mantle.
</P>
<P>
   Daughters Karenna and Kristin are chief ambassadors until Gore
and wife Tipper arrive at the Democratic National Convention later
this week.
</P>
<P>
   One is the family's political heir apparent; the other makes her
political debut. The sisters kick off their week of campaigning
with a common theme: To get politically blase Generation Xers
excited enough about their dad's run to actually vote.
</P>
<P>
   First stop Sunday was an afternoon volunteering at the Los
Angeles Regional Food Bank. The message: Gen-Xers are ''the most
active generation in American history'' when it comes to
volunteering to help the poor, the homeless, the environment, all
sorts of causes, Kristin Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   But, ''when it comes to voting, unfortunately we are the most
apathetic generation,'' she said, after the sisters joined college
students to help sort donated food and other items that will be
sent to needy people. ''We need to volunteer and we need to vote.''
</P>
<P>
   The sisters never mentioned their father by name, but urged that
young people vote for candidates who support the same societal
improvements that, by volunteering, youths themselves do.
</P>
<P>
   ''This election is really, really important,'' said Karenna Gore
Schiff. ''We must take this spirit that the volunteers showed here
to make our country a better place, and demand the same of our
government. We have to make sure that our public servants are on
the same side, working for the same goals.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if her involvement would go beyond voting, to actually
running for office, Schiff laughed and said, ''No plans for that.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I look forward to when I have more people in my generation
running,'' she said. ''I don't think we should all come from the
same family so Kristin and I are campaigning for some fresh
blood.''
</P>
<P>
   After an afternoon volunteering, the sisters were primed for
some fun, at a Hollywood party featuring the popular Goo Goo Dolls
Sunday night. Tuesday, they join a voter registration rally thrown
by MTV's Choose or Lose.
</P>
<P>
   For Schiff, 27 and a new mother living in New York City,
campaigning has become old hat. She was critiquing her father's
political speeches in her teens. Now she has become an astute
adviser to her dad, who says her instincts have ''nearly perfect
pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   But this week marks the political debut of Kristin Gore, 23, a
comedy writer for Fox TV's hip sci-fi cartoon Futurama. Millions
will get their first good glimpse of the Gores' second daughter
Thursday night, when she introduces her mother on the convention
floor.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's two youngest children, still fiercely protected from the
public eye, will spend the convention more enjoying themselves than
in front of TV cameras. Sarah, 21, is a student at Harvard. Albert
III, who at age 6 was hit by a car and almost died, is now a
17-year-old, football-loving high school senior.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was groomed for politics by his late father, Sen. Albert
Gore Sr.
</P>
<P>
   But family matriarch Pauline, now 88, may have influenced her
son even more, and she will be at his side Thursday as he accepts
his party's presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Pauline Gore, one of the first women to graduate from Vanderbilt
Law School, taught her son from an early age that men and women are
equal. She also introduced her son to environmentalism, his
champion cause, and advised him to be a pragmatic politician.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's sister Nancy died at age 46 of lung cancer, an experience
that prompted Gore to speak out against smoking. Nancy's husband
Frank Hunger remains one of Gore's closest confidants. The
Mississippi lawyer, who strategizes for Gore behind the scenes,
arrived at the convention this weekend.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-13-00 2021 </TRAILER>
