<HEADLINE> Del. Racing Halted by Bomb Threat  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   STANTON, Del. (AP) -- Racing at Delaware Park was suspended
Sunday because of a bomb threat, state police said.
</P>
<P>
   The track was evacuated and three races were canceled when a
caller dialed 911 about 2:40 p.m. and reported that two bombs had
been placed at the track, state police said.
</P>
<P>
   A bomb-sniffing dog was called to search the premises. No
explosives were found.
</P>
<P>
   The phone call was traced to a pay phone on the property and
troopers identified a suspect from evidence at the scene, said Cpl.
Walter W. Newton of the Delaware State Police. He declined to
provide specifics about the nature of the evidence.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect, Kenneth Pierson, 47, of Wilmington, was located at
the slot area inside the park, state police said. He was arrested
and booked on a charge of terroristic threatening.
</P>
</TEXT>
