<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Campaign Polls Show Diverse Numbers  </HEADLINE>
By WILL LESTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Polls taken just before the Democratic
National Convention offer a picture of the presidential race to
suit any taste, from a dead heat to a narrowing of George W. Bush's
lead to a big Bush advantage among likely voters.
</P>
<P>
   Several surveys of registered voters show Republican Bush with
about a 10-point lead over Democrat Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   One poll out Sunday suggested the race was roughly even among
registered voters, however, and another suggested Bush is ahead by
16 points among likely voters.
</P>
<P>
   An NBC-Wall Street Journal poll showed Bush with 44 percent
support and Gore with 41 percent, with the remainder for others or
undecided. An NBC-Journal poll released before the Republican
convention showed Bush with a 6 percent edge. The latest NBC poll
of 802 registered voters was conducted Thursday and Friday and had
an error margin of 3.5 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   A CNN-USA Today-Gallup poll out Sunday showed Bush at 55
percent, and Gore at 39 percent among likely voters, a group that
tends to lean more Republican. That poll of 641 likely voters was
taken Thursday and Friday and had a 4 point error margin.
</P>
<P>
   About a quarter of those polled in the NBC-Journal poll said the
selection of Sen. Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut as Gore's
Democratic running mate made them feel more positively about Gore,
while seven of 10 said it made no difference. That's about the same
percentage who said that of Dick Cheney, Bush's running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Several polls out late last week, including those by ABC, CBS
and Newsweek, gave Bush about a 10-point lead over Gore among
registered voters, down slightly from the polls immediately after
the GOP convention. A likely voter poll by CNN-Time put the margin
for Bush slightly higher.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's lead after the July 31-Aug. 3 GOP convention ranged from
11 points among registered voters to 18 points among likely voters.
</P>
<P>
   ''We fully expect the polls to tighten significantly after the
Democratic Convention and expect a very tight race in the fall,''
said Bush spokesman Ray Sullivan. ''Mr. Gore may even take a slight
lead coming out of the convention.... But Governor Bush's
consistent lead in the national polls shows his positive, unifying
message and focus on important issues like education, Social
Security, national defense and tax relief is winning over voters.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats found encouragement in the polls, however, both in the
shrinking margin in polls that show Bush ahead, and in two recent
polls that showed the race about even, the NBC-Journal poll and a
Fox News-Opinion Dynamics poll out Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''All the polls show that momentum is going toward
Gore-Lieberman,'' said Joe Andrew, Democratic national chairman.
''The horse-race numbers vary, but they are better than they were a
week ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're in a position where just a decent convention puts us
where we want to be -- at one point we thought it would take a great
convention,'' said Andrew. ''After the convention, we need to be
where we were before the conventions. We need to have this race
back within the margin of error.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew said a close race would help Democrats energize their
voters, an area where Republicans have had an advantage much of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   The volatility in the polls is not unexpected because of the
rapid changes that come during the two political conventions --
notably the selection of running mates -- and the generally low
amount of attention voters paid to the campaign up to that point,
veteran analysts say.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-13-00 2038 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000813.0103 </DOCNO>
