<HEADLINE> Puerto Ricans Protest Navy Exercises  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) -- About 1,000 protesters joined hands
along the fence outside a U.S. Navy training ground in Puerto Rico
on Sunday to protest military exercises under way there.
</P>
<P>
   Demonstrators also hung white ribbons and anti-Navy signs on the
chain-link fence in Vieques. Military police on the other side
videotaped the demonstrators as they chanted, ''Vieques, yes, Navy,
no!'' and sang protest songs.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the protest was peaceful and that none of the
protesters tried to enter the training ground during the
demonstration.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy owns two-thirds of the 5 mile-by-20mile island and has
used it for exercises and weapons storage since the 1940s.
Resentment over the Navy's presence flared in April 1999, when a
U.S. Marine Corps jet dropped two bombs off target, killing a
civilian security guard working in the bombing range.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters camped out on the bombing range and thwarted further
exercises until federal marshals forcibly cleared them out in May.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has promised to order the Navy to leave by May
2003 if the island's 9,400 residents vote in a referendum to expel
it. Exercises are to continue with dummy bombs and shells until the
vote, which is expected next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-13-00 2043 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
