<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Haitian community outraged that paramilitary leader allowed to live in Queens. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP)- The fact that a feared, former-paramilitary
leader from Haiti is living amongst his fellow countrymen in Queens
has outraged his neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   About 30 people gathered outside Emmanuel Constant's Queens home
Saturday morning, to angrily protest his presence in the United
States, according to newspaper reports.
</P>
<P>
   Constant founded the Front for Advancement and Progress of
Haiti, the political arm of the military group that deposed Haitian
President Jean-Bertrand Aristide in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The group is accused of killing up to 4,000 people and
committing hundreds of human rights violations, including beatings
and rapes.
</P>
<P>
   A coalition of Haitian and human rights groups have tried to
convince the U.S. government to extradite Constant back to the
Caribbean nation to face trial.
</P>
<P>
   Constant was arrested in New York in 1996, and detained by the
Immigration and Naturalization Service for a year. He was abruptly
released a year later.
</P>
</TEXT>
