<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 9 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Sunday, Aug. 13, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Study: TV Coverage Favors Republicans
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- TV networks have given George W. Bush more favorable
coverage than Al Gore, both during the GOP convention and throughout the
presidential race, a new analysis finds. Still, Republicans are worried the
networks will give the Democratic National Convention more TV time this week
than they gave the GOP gathering in Philadelphia two weeks ago. The study, being
released tomorrow by the Center for Media and Public Affairs, examined 72
stories that aired during the Republican National Convention, July 31-Aug. 3, on
the ABC, CBS and NBC evening news. It found that 60 percent of people quoted in
stories praised Bush's policies, political skills or personal character, while
80 percent of people quoted criticized Gore.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
N.J. Roads, Bridges Washed Out
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SPARTA, N.J. (AP) -- Residents of two northern New Jersey towns were
evacuated today and others were put on alert in the wake of torrential downpours
that washed out bridges and roads, broke through a dam and prompted fears of
mudslides. Officials estimated that yesterday's downpour, which dumped more than
14 inches of rain on the area around Sparta, caused hundreds of million of
dollars in damage. The storm caused about $166 million in damage in Sussex
County alone, the area hit hardest by the storm.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Paraguay VP Vote Too Close To Call
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) -- Paraguay's election for a successor to its slain
vice president was too close to call today, with exit polls showing only the
slightest of margins between the late politician's son and the opposition
candidate. The special, one-office election is seen as chance by the opposition
to end the ruling Colorado Party's 53-year rule in this South American country's
shaky democracy. The post of vice president has been empty since Luis Argana was
gunned down in the street in March 1999.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Evacuees Go Home, but Fires Still Threaten
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BOULDER, Mont. (AP) -- Hundreds of evacuees were allowed back into homes in
the Elkhorn Mountains today, but wildfires still threatened more than 2,000
homes across the state. So far this fire season, more than 365,000 acres of
Montana has burned -- an area larger than the city of Los Angeles -- and 169
buildings, including more than 50 homes, have burned. Firefighters had gotten a
break from the weather yesterday and had made progress toward containing the
fires, said Larry Humphrey, the area's incident commander.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Ford: Problem Tires Made During Strike
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Many of the 6.5 million Firestone tires being
recalled were made during a strike at the company's Decatur, Ill., plant, Ford
Motor Co. said today. The tires are under investigation in hundreds of crashes
that caused at least 46 deaths. Ford conducted an analysis of its Firestone
tires and the complaints it had received to pin down where the tires were made.
The number of complaints was 10 times higher for the 15-inch ATX tires made in
Decatur than for the Wilderness tires, said Jason Vines, Ford's vice president
of communications. At the time, union workers at the plant were on strike, and
the plant was operating with replacement workers and managers.
Bridgestone/Firestone said the strike had nothing to do with the problems.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gore Would Seek Clinton's Counsel
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CLEVELAND (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore, at the very moment he is trying to
emerge from President Clinton's shadow, said today he would not hesitate to seek
Clinton's counsel if he succeeds him. ''Why would I rule that out?'' Gore said
in an interview with The Associated Press. The vice president, battling
Republican attempts to shackle him to Clinton's personal scandals, also said he
would serve his own term in the Oval Office ''according to the highest values.''
Gore spoke on the eve of Clinton's valedictory tomorrow night to the Democratic
National Convention in Los Angeles.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
National Gas Price Average Drops
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CAMARILLO, Calif. (AP) -- The average price of gasoline fell 7.48 cents a
gallon nationwide in the past three weeks to $1.53, continuing its decline after
record highs in some areas in June. The slide began after suppliers rushed
gasoline to the Midwest to solve distribution problems in the region, analyst
Trilby Lundberg said today. However, price declines in the next few weeks may
slow or stop altogether, since summer is still in full swing, Lundberg said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Indians Defeat Mariners 10-4
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- Travis Fryman homered, doubled and drove in four runs and the
Cleveland Indians took advantage of Seattle's sloppy fielding to defeat the
Mariners 10-4 today. The win pulled Cleveland into a tie with Oakland for the AL
wild-card spot.
</P>
