<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taiwan Leader Plans Low-Key US Stop  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID BRISCOE
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Taiwanese President Chen Shui-bian waved to
well-wishers outside his hotel Sunday but made no statement and
planned no official meetings during an overnight visit to this city
where Democrats prepared for their national convention.
</P>
<P>
   Chen slipped quietly into the Los Angeles area with no red
carpet or government welcome mat.
</P>
<P>
   China protested the 16-hour stopover, while the top Democrat on
the House International Relations Committee complained that the
Clinton administration pressured Chen into not meeting with several
members of Congress attending the convention.
</P>
<P>
   It was Chen's first venture abroad as president. The two-week
trip, which also will include stops in the Caribbean, Central
America and Africa, is aimed at strengthening ties with Taiwan's
dwindling number of diplomatic allies. The United States does not
have formal diplomatic relations with Taiwan, but 29 small nations
do.
</P>
<P>
   The trip comes amid continuing tension over China's claim that
Taiwan is part of its territory. Chen has tried to improve
unofficial U.S ties while offering conciliatory gestures and summit
invitations to China.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Sam Gejdenson of Connecticut, the ranking Democrat on the
International Relations Committee, had invited about a dozen
Democratic and Republican committee members and others to meet with
Chen at a private residence in Santa Monica, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   But Chen declined the invitation. While officials in Taiwan
downplayed the cancellation, Gejdenson complained that the State
Department and White House had ''pressured (him) to refrain from
meeting with Congress during his visit'' and keep a low profile.
</P>
<P>
   A committee staff member, Amos Hochstein, said Sunday that 12 to
15 members of Congress had been expected to attend. With several
lawmakers in town for the convention ''we thought it would be a
good opportunity to meet with him,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department publicly objected to such a meeting last
week.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and most other countries recognize only
mainland China, which claims that Taiwan is part of its territory.
</P>
<P>
   Beijing had warned that even the brief stop on U.S. soil could
severely damage U.S. ties with China. In 1995, a more extensive
visit by then-Taiwanese President Lee Teng-hui was followed by
Chinese missile tests near Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Just getting permission to stop in the United States was an
important victory for Chen. In Taiwan, it was viewed as a sign that
Washington trusted Chen would not do anything to disrupt America's
delicate relations with China.
</P>
<P>
   Coincidentally, Chen's airplane was parked about 600 feet from
the Air Force One jet that brought President Clinton to town for
the Democratic National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwanese Foreign Ministry official Wu Tzu-dan declined comment
on the cancellation. Asked if Chen still might meet with any
members of Congress individually, Wu said he would only ''wave to
them from afar.''
</P>
<P>
   ''President Chen will spend most of his time in the hotel'' in
Long Beach where a banquet was scheduled for the Taiwanese leader
and his delegation.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dana Rohrabacher, R-Calif., in an interview with Associated
Press Television Network, accused the administration of ''groveling
before a dictator'' in its lack of a warm reception for Chen, who
is democratically elected leader of Taiwan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-13-00 2109 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000813.0110 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 21:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 16 Die in Kashmir Blasts, Fighting  </HEADLINE>
By BINOO JOSHI
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAMMU, India (AP) -- A series of explosions and gunbattles rocked
the Himalayan province of Kashmir on Sunday, leaving 16 people dead
and dozens injured in stepped-up violence before India's
Independence Day celebrations, police said.
</P>
<P>
   In the village of Kud, two land mines exploded under buses
carrying Indian paramilitary troops, authorities said. Six troops
were killed and 40 injured, 10 critically.
</P>
<P>
   The Pakistan-based Hezb-ul Mujahedeen -- the largest of the
Muslim rebel groups here -- claimed responsibility for the mine
explosions at Kud, 50 miles north of Jammu, the winter capital of
Indian-controlled Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   The group said it would increase attacks against Indian troops
here. The province is the seat of an Islamic insurgency that has
left 25,000 people dead in the last 11 years.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are committed to end Indian rule in Kashmir and our
activities will escalate,'' Salim Hashmi, a Hezb-ul Mujahedeen
spokesman in the Pakistani capital, Islamabad, told The Associated
Press by telephone.
</P>
<P>
   The buses were part of a convoy carrying security personnel to
Srinagar, 185 miles to the north, ahead of Tuesday's Independence
Day celebration. Militants fighting Indian security forces in
Kashmir usually increase violence against the government during the
run-up to the Aug. 15 celebration, and separatist guerrilla groups
have vowed to wreck the festivities again this year.
</P>
<P>
   Also Sunday, an army foot patrol sighted militants in a remote,
mountainous area 160 miles north of Jammu and opened fire on them.
An ensuing gunbattle left 10 rebels dead, Maj. Gen. P.P.S. Bindra
said. No army casualties were reported.
</P>
<P>
   The army described the killings as a major success in its
intensified anti-militancy operations on the eve of Indian
Independence Day.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in the province, three smaller explosions injured two
people Sunday. In Srinagar, police sealed an area around the Bakshi
Stadium where the Independence Day parade is held every year.
Militants usually fire rockets and grenades toward the stadium to
disrupt the celebrations.
</P>
<P>
   Police set up metal barricades on the roads to check all
vehicles in the area. Passengers on buses were frisked with metal
detectors. Many residents stayed indoors.
</P>
<P>
   The mountainous province of Kashmir is divided between India and
Pakistan, both of which claim it in its entirety. The Islamic
guerrillas want Indian-controlled Kashmir to break away from
heavily Hindu India and either remain independent or become part of
mostly Muslim Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan's army ruler Gen. Pervez Musharraf on Sunday pledged to
continue support for the uprising in Kashmir during a speech to
celebrate his country's Independence Day, which falls on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Pakistan stands united with their Kashmiri brothers and
sisters in their just cause,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   India accuses Islamabad of supporting and arming the militants,
a charge the government here denies. Pakistan insists it only gives
moral support to the Kashmiris.
</P>
<P>
   Attacks here increased after Hezb-ul Mujahedeen called off a
brief cease-fire this week. The group wanted India to involve
Pakistan in talks on resolving the Kashmir dispute, but India
refused.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, militants set off two powerful bombs in downtown
Srinagar, killing 14 soldiers and journalists and wounding 25
others. On Saturday, suspected guerrillas lobbed a grenade near a
mosque in Srinagar, wounding two Hungarian and two Kashmiri women.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
