<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Leaf, Moreno Likely to Get a Start  </HEADLINE>
By BERNIE WILSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO (AP) -- Although he was shaded from the afternoon sun,
San Diego Chargers coach Mike Riley was on the hot seat Sunday
about how he's going to use his quarterbacks in the final two
exhibition games.
</P>
<P>
   Will Ryan Leaf, pegged as the franchise's savior two summers ago
before being sidelined by his bad-boy act and a shoulder injury,
get a start as he continues his solid comeback? How about
second-stringer Moses Moreno, the local product who's made just one
career regular-season start?
</P>
<P>
   Riley was short on specifics but said the coaching staff will
consider all scenarios leading up to Friday night's game at
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The line of questioning came up after starter Jim Harbaugh was
ineffective in the first three possessions in Saturday night's 31-7
win over the Minnesota Vikings.
</P>
<P>
   Riley said it certainly wasn't all Harbaugh's fault, because
receivers blew routes, the protection wasn't good and the Chargers'
running game went nowhere -- they had 0 rushing yards at halftime.
The Chargers had just 35 yards total offense at halftime, but led
14-7, thanks largely to rookie Ronney Jenkins' 86-yard kickoff
return for a TD.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to evaluate it some more and not jump to any
conclusions right now, just stay status quo,'' Riley said. ''It's
probably not necessary to do anything right away on that. But we
will look at it. We are in a competitive deal here now, so
production is very important.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley also said the Chargers (2-0) are ''trying to be
equitable,'' and someone other than Harbaugh could start against
the Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   ''That will definitely be one of the things that we'll look at
and really, that's not a reflection on where Jim is,'' he said.
''I'm not going say that we've made a change in our starter, but in
order to get somebody else some earlier turns, we may change the
rotation around.''
</P>
<P>
   Leaf and Moreno both played well Saturday night. Leaf was
11-of-18 for 80 yards and led the Chargers on two scoring drives,
one of just 5 yards following an interception, and a 72-yard drive
using the no-huddle offense that was capped by a field goal. Moreno
threw the Chargers' only TD pass of the night and finished 6-of-8
for 82 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Harbaugh was 2-of-5 for 1 yard with one interception and a
fumble, which San Diego recovered. In two games he is 7-of-13 for
34 yards with no TDs and one interception.
</P>
<P>
   Riley said the Chargers should have a starter picked, or be real
close, by the final exhibition game against Arizona on Aug. 25.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we want to take one more hard look at somebody, then that
person may get extended time in that game,'' he said. ''I don't
think we're at that point yet, but we're going to be forced here
pretty soon to make that decision, and maybe we can get it done by
that game.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley said one consideration in the quarterback rotation is
giving the quarterbacks work with starting center Roman Fortin.
Once Fortin's out, rookie Jason Thomas takes over.
</P>
<P>
   ''The hard part is who to give the opportunity to, really, with
that first-string line,'' he said. ''I just think that is a
critical part of the ballgame. How we do that is important for the
quarterbacks to have an opportunity to show what they can do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
