<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cardinal Urges Help for Poor  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Cardinal Roger Mahony, who will deliver an
invocation at Monday's opening of the Democratic National
Convention, told Catholic delegates on Sunday that children's lives
are threatened ''both in the womb and in our neighborhoods.''
</P>
<P>
   Acceptance of the invitation to speak from the convention podium
is a departure from recent years. Catholic leaders have turned down
such offers in decisions widely seen as a reactions to Democratic
support of abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   Mahony, the archbishop of the Los Angeles diocese, the nation's
largest with nearly 4 million Catholics, told about 350 people
during Mass on Sunday at the Wilshire Grand Hotel that society
faces three main threats:
</P>
<P>
   --To human life from legalized abortion, capital punishment and
doctor-assisted suicide.
</P>
<P>
   --To human dignity from the growing gap between rich and poor,
and a scarcity of affordable housing, health care, child care and
quality education.
</P>
<P>
   --And to human rights from exploitation of immigrant workers,
discrimination, racism and a minimum wage that is insufficient to
''support a family in dignity.''
</P>
<P>
   ''In the end, God will not rely on polling data to judge our
fidelity to the Gospels,'' he told the delegates.
</P>
<P>
   ''God will not convene focus groups to determine our moral
integrity or our ethical fitness,'' he said. ''Instead, we will
face a self-examination that is both simple and stark: Whatever we
did for the least of those among us, we did for God.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The challenges that stand before us are many,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One such challenge, he said, is ''to reinvigorate a deeper sense
of promoting the common good, rather than an exaggerated sense of
individualism.''
</P>
<P>
   Mahony has been a leading voice on church positions against
capital punishment and abortion. This year he urged Gov. Gray Davis
to declare a moratorium on capital punishment for an investigation
of possible inequities and biases.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
