<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressThe Rev. Artur Erikson:
<TEXT>
<P>
   STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) -- The Rev. Artur Erikson, a popular
Lutheran singer who wrote more than 600 songs, has died. He was 82.
</P>
<P>
   Erikson died Thursday at his home in Gagnef, 120 miles northwest
of the capital, Stockholm, according to Swedish media reports.
</P>
<P>
   Erikson got his start in music from his father, a singing
minister who often took his son along as he toured the country. The
boy made his stage debut at age 12.
</P>
<P>
   In 1942, Erikson became a minister in Sweden's dominant Lutheran
church and took his own act on the road for 15 years. He made
frequent radio appearances starting in 1956 and became a household
name in the early 1960s as a guest on Sweden's most popular
television talk show, Hyland's Corner.
</P>
<P>
   Erikson, whose repertoire spanned from gospel to psalms, topped
the local charts in 1970, with his song ''To My Sister.'' Erikson
recorded and produced 28 albums, earning six gold records.
Don Ettlinger:
</P>
<P>
   NYACK, N.Y. (AP) -- Don Ettlinger, a writer for film, television
and theater, died Aug. 7 at a hospital here. He was 86.
</P>
<P>
   Ettlinger was born in Detroit and attended Stanford University
and the University of Chicago. While still an undergraduate, he was
hired by 20th Century Fox in Hollywood and, at 21, became one of
the youngest contract writers on the Fox lot.
</P>
<P>
   One of Ettlinger's early projects, written with Karl Tunberg,
was the 1938 film ''Rebecca of Sunnybrook Farm,'' starring Shirley
Temple. With Tunberg, Ettlinger also wrote ''Shipyard Sally''
(1940), which was based on a story by Gracie Fields, Tom Geraghty
and Val Valentine, and was a writer of ''The Great American
Broadcast'' (1941).
</P>
<P>
   In the early days of television, Ettlinger worked for Studio One
and Kraft Television Theater.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his wife, Katrina he is survived by two
daughters, a son and four grandchildren.
Claude Hope:
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Claude Hope, a horticulturist known among many
gardening enthusiasts as the father of the impatiens -- the No. 1
bedding plant in America, died July 14 in Costa Rica. He was 93.
</P>
<P>
   Hope died at his 200-acre farm in the Costa Rican village of
Dulce Nombre de Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s, Hope, through years of breeding and hybridizing,
turned the unruly impatiens of the wild into the compact, reliable
mass of blooms that now poke their heads up -- too often, its
detractors say -- in yards, window boxes and public spaces across
North America.
Pedro Lavoura:
</P>
<P>
   LISBON, Portugal (AP) -- Pedro Lavoura, a Venezuelan midfielder
playing for Portugal's Sporting Braga, was killed Sunday when his
car veered off the road and slammed into a wall, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Two other passengers also died in the accident that occurred
near Aveiro, about 130 miles north of Lisbon.
</P>
<P>
   The three men were ejected from the car, a Porsche. The engine
went up in flames about 55 yards away from the wall, according to
police. It was not immediately known who was driving.
</P>
<P>
   Lavoura, 26, began playing in Portugal with Anadia, a
second-division club, in 1994. He joined Braga last year.
G. Warren Schloat Jr.:
</P>
<P>
   ESCONDIDO, Calif. (AP) -- G. Warren Schloat Jr., a writer and
illustrator of children's books who also worked on several of the
classic films from the Walt Disney Studios, died on July 30 at a
hospital here. He was 86.
</P>
<P>
   Schloat wrote and illustrated 22 children's books, including
''Andy's Wonderful Telescope,'' ''Fay Gow, a Boy of Hong Kong'' and
''Playtime for You.''
</P>
<P>
   He also had worked his way up the ranks at Walt Disney Studios,
first as an animator and later as a story editor, where he
contributed to classics like ''Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs''
and ''Dumbo.''
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Virginia, two sons, a brother and
five grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
