<HEADLINE> Film, TV and theater writer Don Ettlinger dies at 86  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NYACK, N.Y. (AP) - Don Ettlinger, a writer for film, television
and theater, died Aug. 7 at a hospital here. He was 86.
</P>
<P>
   Ettlinger was born in Detroit and attended Stanford University
and the University of Chicago. While still an undergraduate, he was
hired by 20th Century Fox in Hollywood and, at 21, became one of
the youngest contract writers on the Fox lot.
</P>
<P>
   One of Ettlinger's early projects, written with Karl Tunberg,
was the 1938 film ''Rebecca of Sunnybrook Farm,'' starring Shirley
Temple. With Tunberg, Ettlinger also wrote ''Shipyard Sally''
(1940), which was based on a story by Gracie Fields, Tom Geraghty
and Val Valentine, and was a writer of ''The Great American
Broadcast'' (1941).
</P>
<P>
   In the early days of television, Ettlinger worked for Studio One
and Kraft Television Theater.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his wife, Katrina he is survived by two
daughters, a son and four grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
