<HEADLINE> Some Delegates Use Nonunion Hotels  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY MARGASAK
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Democratic National Convention officials
tried to house participants in unionized hotels for this week, but
when those rooms ran out, they resorted to booking them into
nonunion facilities.
</P>
<P>
   The unions, however, are not complaining, even though one
hostelry is the nonunion Loews in Santa Monica that is owned by a
major contributor to the Democratic Party and has been the scene of
a bitter union organizing drive.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are not even slightly'' upset with the Democrats, John W.
Wilhelm, general president of the Hotel Employees and Restaurant
Employees International Union, said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   At an afternoon pep rally at a downtown Los Angeles hotel, union
representatives handed pink and yellow buttons -- declaring ''We
support Loews workers'' -- to labor delegates attending the
Democratic convention.
</P>
<P>
   More than half of the 1,500 labor delegates waved signs, wore
colored T-shirts with the name of their union, and cheered AFL-CIO
President John Sweeney as he exhorted them to elect Democratic
candidates this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have set the table for restoring the voices of working
families,'' Sweeney declared.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney also attended a later demonstration at the Loews, which
is owned by Jonathan Tisch, a major Democratic contributor.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of union members rallied in favor of the Loews Hotel
workers, demanding they have the right to join a union. Several
speakers criticized Tisch.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is a moral challenge,'' the Rev. Jesse Jackson told
reporters after the rally. ''The party would do a great service to
give him his money back.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Paul Wellstone, D-Minn., said: ''Mr. Tisch, I know you've
been a big contributor to the Democratic Party. But the Democratic
Party must be there with the employees, must be there with the
workers.''
</P>
<P>
   The AFL-CIO and most major unions have endorsed the ticket of
Vice President Al Gore and Sen. Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut.
But the rally site has its own irony.
</P>
<P>
   Tisch, president and chief executive officer of Loews Hotels
Corp., is also a ''trustee'' donor of the Lieberman-led, centrist
Democratic Leadership Counsel. The tax-exempt group would not
disclose the contribution required to be a ''trustee.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of Tisch's fellow large donors as well as Jackson and
several fiscally conservative Democratic House members are staying
at the Loews. However, the Kennedy-led Democratic Congressional
Campaign Committee moved its operations to a unionized hotel
nearby.
</P>
<P>
   ''There were no other rooms,'' DCCC spokesman Eric Smith said of
the nonunion bookings. ''Months ago people were optimistic this
labor situation would have been resolved.''
</P>
<P>
   The hotel-restaurant union officials estimate only 30 percent of
the rooms in the Los Angeles area are in unionized hotels.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're asking the Democrats to support the hotel workers
actively,'' Wilhelm said. ''The labor dispute erupted late,
beginning in late May.''
</P>
<P>
   Tisch, in a letter to the workers, said, ''Our position is
simple: The employees of this hotel should decide on union
representation.'' He said that ''the best way to do this is by an
election. This will ensure a fair, secret ballot election so that
employees can vote their wishes free from intimidation and
pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   The union opposes an election, preferring that a new bargaining
unit be recognized when a majority of the workers sign union cards.
Union officials said workers would feel coerced in an election
procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Each side has accused the other of unwarranted pressure.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel-restaurant union contends a Loews-hired consulting
firm has intimidated workers to persuade them not to unionize.
Management has ''held captive audience meetings'' where workers
were forced to ''listen to anti-union harangues,'' said David Koff,
a research analyst with the union.
</P>
<P>
   ''Workers were threatened with arrest and with losing their
jobs,'' Koff said.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, Richard Mintz, a spokesman for Loews Hotels
Corp., contended the union has contacted potential members ''in the
middle of the night, screamed at them as they left the property.''
</P>
<P>
   Mintz said wage scales at the hotel range from $7 to $10 an
hour, but the figures do not include gratuities.
</P>
<P>
   Union officials said their contracts for hotel workers here
range from $9.50 to $11.50 per hour.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
