<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kapler Extends Hitting Streak  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas (AP) -- Gabe Kapler extended his hitting streak
to 26 games, longest in the majors this season, with a single in
the sixth inning Sunday night for the Texas Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   In his first two at-bats against Boston, Kapler flied out and
hit a sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   Kapler set the Rangers' franchise record on Saturday night when
he went 3-for-3 against the Red Sox and extended the streak to 25
games. The Texas-Washington record had been held by Mickey Rivers,
who hit in 24 straight games during the 1980 season.
</P>
<P>
   The last major leaguer with a hitting streak of more than 25
games was Shannon Stewart, who hit in 26 straight games for Toronto
in August 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
