<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 22:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Talks About Peace Summit  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- President Clinton said Sunday that for
Israelis and Palestinians the inconclusive Camp David peace summit
was like having a tooth drilled without anesthesia.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton mostly put partisan politics on hold during a speech to
members of the American-Israel Public Affairs Committee, a Jewish
lobbying organization. Clinton is in town for the Democratic
National Convention, where he is a featured speaker Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   He said he understood why both sides left the hardest issues for
last in their gradual pursuit of peace.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's kind of like going to the dentist without anybody to
deaden your gums,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that he was still disappointed by the failure to get a
peace deal despite round-the-clock negotiations last month.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't want to sugarcoat it. I wanted an agreement and we
didn't get one, but I can tell you we made a lot of progress.''
</P>
<P>
   One major stumbling block was the fate of Jerusalem, as Clinton
acknowledged to the crowd at an outdoor party at a Hollywood movie
lot.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is a holy city, but it has caused a hellish lot of
problems,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   He promised to keep working at it through the remaining six
months of his term.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the meantime we will continue to stand with Israel, as we
have throughout my tenure,'' Clinton said to loud applause.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
