<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 22:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Floods cause millions in damages, governor to have estimate on Monday </HEADLINE>
By AMY WESTFELDT
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPARTA, N.J. (AP) - State officials estimated that Saturday's
heavy rains and flooding caused several million dollars worth of
damage in northern New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Bridges washed out, roads collapsed and dams burst after the
region was hit with a deluge of water.
</P>
<P>
   Peter McDonough, spokesman for Gov. Christie Whitman, said
officials would have a preliminary estimate of the damage on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman flew over the mud-soaked counties Sunday morning to view
the destruction.
</P>
<P>
   In Sussex County alone, the storm caused about $166 million
worth of damage, said Phil Morlock, the county's health and public
safety administrator.
</P>
<P>
   Morlock said $80 million of that total was damage to bridges and
roads. The rest was to private property, including in Newton, where
water mains were destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Rivoli, director of the Warren County Office of
Emergency Management, said water was breaching the Musconetcong
River Sunday afternoon. The river flows out of Sussex County and
borders Morris and Warren counties.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of Hackettstown were being evacuated and other towns
were on alert.
</P>
<P>
   But by 10 p.m. Sunday night, everything had calmed down and the
emergency management offices had closed, according the Warren
County communications center.
</P>
<P>
   The National Weather Service had issued a flash flood warning
Sunday for parts of Morris, Warren, Hunterdon and Sussex counties,
due to river flooding.
</P>
<P>
   In Stanhope, two sides of the small dam on Furnace Pond washed
away. Police Chief Douglas Waldron said only a small section was
left this morning and the water was flowing heavily around it.
</P>
<P>
   As of 9:30 p.m., he said crews were collecting barrels from a
factory that flooded. The company manufactured paper with adhesive
backing and workers were trying to ensure nothing hazardous got
into the water, although the company moved most of its materials
before the factory flooded.
</P>
<P>
   In Sparta, one of the hardest-hit areas, three roads and three
bridges were destroyed by the torrential downpours, which dumped 14
inches of rain on the township, said Police Sgt. Russell Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Residents who live in a small section of Main Street were
evacuated Sunday because fire officials feared a mudslide down a
mountain that rises above the township. Firefighters ferried
residents across metal ladders and ropes set up across fast-moving
currents.
</P>
<P>
   Several homes were blocked on one side by mud from another slide
and on the other by a road that had turned into a brown river.
</P>
<P>
   One firefighter carried a small, white dog in his arms while
balancing himself on a tree trunk that had fallen across a stream.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm feeling relieved that I'm on this side and that my kids
are here,'' said Tori Monahan, 33, with her daughters, Katie, 1,
and Kelly, 3.
</P>
<P>
   The force of Saturday's rain and flooding burst the dam on
Sparta's Seneca Lake, a small, private lake surrounded by homes in
Sussex County, the northernmost part of the state.
</P>
<P>
   No injuries were reported. Police tape surrounded the small
beach at the empty lake, which smelled of dead fish Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Brunetti, 43, said the lake emptied of its thousands of
gallons of water in one hour Saturday evening. It was ''just a big
hole, and the dock floating away,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   About 28 families spent the night in an emergency shelter in
Sparta Township. Steve Wille, a Red Cross volunteer who has lived
here for 30 years, said he'd never seen anything like Saturday's
storm.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've all seen sheets of rain for five, 10, 15 minutes. This
continued for hour after hour after hour after hour,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Preskar Earl said the combination of flooding and downed
trees diverted two ponds in the back yard of her Sparta home into a
stream that runs behind her house.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was just water and trees and boulders coming everywhere,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   In Newton, water supply was a major concern as rushing water
took out the town's two water mains along the Sparta Glen, said
Town Manager Camille Furgiulele.
</P>
<P>
   Furgiulele said a nearby well was tapped to alleviate the
problem, but that the supplementary source would only yield about
20 percent of the usual supply of 1 million gallons a day.
</P>
<P>
   Repair crews were unable to reach the water mains because roads
were flooded and a bridge to access the area had washed out.
</P>
<P>
   Furgiulele said although there are only about 8,000 residents in
Newton, the county seat, up to 20,000 people work there.
</P>
<P>
   Flooding lakes and rivers Saturday washed out bridges in
Jefferson Township and Ogdensburg, and caused road closures in
Morris and Sussex counties.
</P>
<P>
   About 250 customers of GPU Energy were without power Sunday
afternoon in Newton, Sparta and Flemington, said Ron Morano, a
company spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Power had been restored to most of the 10,000 customers who were
without it Saturday, he said.
</P>
<P>
   An 11-year-old boy was struck by lightning Saturday while
fishing with his family in Middle Township, but wasn't seriously
hurt. The lightning bolt hit a lamp post and traveled down to a
metal railing that the barefoot boy was holding onto.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
