<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 22:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Koreas Reopen Border Liaisons  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PANMUNJOM, South Korea (AP) -- North and South Korea reopened
border liaison offices Monday, four years after they were closed
because of political tensions.
</P>
<P>
   Relations between the two Koreas have warmed significantly since
their leaders held a historic summit in Pyongyang, the North's
capital, in June. In follow-up talks by their deputies in Seoul two
weeks ago, the Koreas agreed to reopen the border liaison offices.
</P>
<P>
   ''This shows that the will of South and North Korea to
faithfully implement their summit agreement is firm,'' South Korean
Unification Minister Park Jae-kyu said at the border village of
Panmunjom, 35 miles north of Seoul.
</P>
<P>
   The liaison offices first opened in 1992 to work as government
channels of dialogue. They closed four years later after a dispute
over a North Korean submarine that washed ashore in South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Two telephone hotlines link the two liaison offices across the
border at Panmunjom, which lies inside the 2.5-mile-wide
Demilitarized Zone separating the two Koreas.
</P>
<P>
   Eight officials from each side will relay messages and conduct
other work in their office for nine hours a day, Seoul's
Unification Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
   The reopening of the liaison offices came a day before the
Koreas were to exchange 100 people each for four days of temporary
reunions with long-lost relatives, the first since 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Since the June summit, the Koreas already have stopped
propaganda broadcasts against each other and agreed to reconnect a
cross-border railway which was cut off just before the start of the
1950-53 Korean War.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
