<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 22:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Raiders 21, Cowboys 20  </HEADLINE>
By JAIME ARON
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas (AP) -- Scott Dreisbach threw a 15-yard touchdown
pass to Willy Tate, then a 2-point conversion to David Dunn with
1:08 left, giving the Oakland Raiders a 21-20 victory over the
Dallas Cowboys on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Raiders (1-1) trailed 17-3 at halftime despite their
regulars thoroughly outplaying the Cowboys' first team. Oakland got
within 17-13, then trailed 20-13 when Dreisbach was intercepted
with little more than three minutes left.
</P>
<P>
   Then Dallas (0-3) showed why it has lost 12 of its last 13
preseason games. The offense went three-and-out, forcing punter
Micah Knorr to kick from his end zone. A short punt gave Dreisbach
a second chance and he cashed it in.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys drove to the Raiders 41, then sent Tim Seder to try
a 58-yard field goal on the game's final play. It was way short and
to the right.
</P>
<P>
   In the first half, Oakland outgained Dallas 222 yards to 80. The
Raiders ran for 146 yards on 21 carries, an average of 7 per try.
</P>
<P>
   The difference, though, was that the Cowboys cashed in on two
turnovers and a big pass interference penalty. Dallas' three
scoring drives went minus-3 yards, 53 yards and 4 yards -- a total
of 54, with 33 coming by penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Cowboys seemed efficient, they weren't.
</P>
<P>
   Their first drive began at the Oakland 27 and went backwards 3
yards before Seder kicked a 47-yard field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Then Chris Warren scored on a 1-yard touchdown run -- without his
left shoe -- on a drive that got a big boost when Charles Woodson
was called for pass interference in the end zone on a ball Wane
McGarity wasn't likely to catch.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Fisher, a fringe candidate in Dallas' cornerback
shuffle, returned an interception 62 yards to set up a 1-yard TD
run by Michael Wiley -- but Dallas needed four plays to score.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher might have scored himself but raised an arm in
celebration at the 12 and was tackled from behind at the 4. Fisher
also had the fourth-quarter interception of Dreisbach.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys quarterback Troy Aikman was just 6-of-14 for 61 yards.
Several of the incompletions were miscommunications with his new
No. 1 target, Joey Galloway, although the speedster still had three
catches for 43 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland's first-half stumbles were varied. Rookie receiver
Marvin Knight fumbled on the first drive and a holding penalty
stunted the second drive. The third ended when rookie Sebastian
Janikowski's 57-yard field goal attempt was blocked.
</P>
<P>
   Janikowski followed with a 47-yarder to make it 10-3. The
Raiders were driving to tie it when Bobby Hoying, under pressure,
threw to an open spot that Fisher ended up filling.
</P>
<P>
   Hoying atoned for his mistake in the third quarter, running for
40 yards on one broken play then capping that drive with a 9-yard
touchdown run that put Oakland within 17-10.
</P>
<P>
   A 44-yard field goal that Janikowski cleared with ease made it
17-13, but Rian Lindell answered with a 19-yarder for Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher's first interception was beat for silliness in the third
quarter when Dallas' James McKnight turned a nice catch into a
54-yard gain -- then fumbled at the Oakland 6. Raiders safety
Brandon Jennings recovered at the 2, then fumbled at midfield.
Dallas' Troy Hambrick picked it up and ran 25 yards, then fell from
exhaustion.
</P>
<P>
   The game was stopped for nearly 10 minutes early in the first
quarter when Raiders receiver Terry Mickens injured his neck after
a catch. He was mobilized and taken to a hospital for observation,
although he was conscious and had feeling in his arms and legs.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas lost receiver Raghib Ismail to a sprained thumb, fullback
Robert Thomas sprained a knee and rookie cornerback Mario Edwards
strained a hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards' injury forced fellow rookie Kareem Larrimore to play
the entire game. Larrimore, a fourth-round draft pick, became a
starter this week when Kevin Smith left camp to contemplate
retiring. Second-round pick Dwayne Goodrich and second-year player
Duane Hawthorne missed the game with injuries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
