<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 22:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Red Sox 4, Rangers 2  </HEADLINE>
By STEPHEN HAWKINS
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas (AP) -- Nomar Garciaparra and Jason Varitek hit
two-run singles in the third inning and the Boston Red Sox beat the
Texas Rangers 4-2 Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Gabe Kapler extended the major leagues' longest hitting streak
this season to 26 games with a sixth-inning single, but Texas had
just five hits. The Rangers have been held to seven hits or less in
four straight games.
</P>
<P>
   Tomo Ohka (1-2) pitched 5 2-3 innings, his longest stint in 12
major league appearances the past two seasons for Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Lowe pitched the ninth for his 26th save in 31
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers couldn't overcome Boston's four-run burst off Kenny
Rogers (11-10).
</P>
<P>
   Rogers had struck out three of the four previous batters,
including Brian Daubach to start the third, before Boston loaded
the bases on an infield hit, a walk and a single.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Everett lined out before Garciaparra singled with two
strikes. Varitek's hit came after Troy O'Leary was hit by a pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Boston's third inning ended when shortstop Royce Clayton made a
diving stab of Bernard Gilkey's hard grounder up the middle and
used a backhand flip to second for the final out.
</P>
<P>
   Texas had the bases loaded in the sixth after Ohka gave up
consecutive two-out walks and was replaced by Rich Garces, who then
got Mike Lamb to foul out.
</P>
<P>
   Boston third baseman Ed Sprague ran down Lamb's popup, using a
full arm extension to make the grab before falling into the Red Sox
dugout and being caught by teammate Israel Alcantara.
</P>
<P>
   Ohka, who allowed just five hits, struck out five and walked
four. Rogers, 2-5 in his last eight starts, left after eight
innings with five strikeouts and a walk.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers got their two runs off Ohka after loading the bases
with no outs in the fourth. Kapler hit a sacrifice fly to center
and Ricky Ledee followed with an RBI single on a high bouncer over
second baseman Mike Lansing.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Rafael Palmeiro drew a walk in the fourth, his seventh base
on balls in the three-game series vs. Boston. ... In his 26-game
hitting streak, Kapler is hitting .371 (39-for-105) with six homers
and 21 RBIs. He finished 1-for-4. ... O'Leary went 0-for-3 and has
just three hits his last 26 at-bats. ... Garciaparra is 15-for-29
(.517) lifetime against Rogers after getting two hits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
