<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Sunday, Aug. 13, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gore Would Seek Clinton's Counsel
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CLEVELAND (AP) -- At the very moment he is trying to emerge from President
Clinton's shadow, Vice President Al Gore said today he would not hesitate to
seek Clinton's counsel if he succeeds him. ''Why would I rule that out?'' Gore
said in an interview with The Associated Press. The vice president, battling
Republican attempts to shackle him to Clinton's personal scandals, also said he
would serve his own term in the Oval Office ''according to the highest values.''
Gore spoke on the eve of Clinton's valedictory tomorrow night to the Democratic
National Convention in Los Angeles.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Koreas Reopen Border Liaisons
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PANMUNJOM, South Korea (AP) -- North and South Korea reopened border liaison
offices Monday, four years after they were closed because of political tensions.
Relations between the two Koreas have warmed significantly since their leaders
held a historic summit in Pyongyang, the North's capital, in June. In follow-up
talks by their deputies in Seoul two weeks ago, the Koreas agreed to reopen the
border liaison offices. The liaison offices first opened in 1992 to work as
government channels of dialogue. They closed four years later after a dispute
over a North Korean submarine that washed ashore in South Korea.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Talks About Peace Summit
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- President Clinton said today that for Israelis and
Palestinians alike the inconclusive Camp David peace summit was like having a
tooth drilled without anesthesia. Clinton, for the most part, put partisan
politics aside during a speech to members of the American-Israel Public Affairs
Committee, a Jewish lobbying organization. The president is in Los Angeles for
the Democratic National Convention, where he's a featured speaker Monday night.
He said he understood why both sides left the most difficult issues for last in
their gradual pursuit of peace.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Ford: Tires Made During Strike
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Many of the 6.5 million Firestone tires being
recalled were made during a strike at the company's Decatur, Ill., plant, Ford
Motor Co. said today. The tires are under investigation in hundreds of crashes
that caused at least 46 deaths. Ford conducted an analysis of its Firestone
tires and the complaints it had received to pin down where the tires were made.
The number of complaints was 10 times higher for the 15-inch ATX tires made in
Decatur than for the Wilderness tires, said Jason Vines, Ford's vice president
of communications. At the time, union workers at the plant were on strike, and
the plant was operating with replacement workers and managers.
Bridgestone/Firestone said the strike had nothing to do with the problems.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Colombia Army Frees 5 Held by Rebels
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BOGOTA (AP) -- Soldiers rescued on Sunday a prominent journalist who had
spent 200 days in captivity, as well as German man and three other hostages
abducted by Colombia's largest guerrilla group, the army said. One guerrilla was
killed in the rescue operation, army Gen. Jorge Morga told reporters. Guillermo
Cortes, 73, host of a popular weekly television news program, owner of a Bogota
soccer team and part-owner of several news-oriented Colombian magazines, was
kidnapped from his home on the capital's wealthy northern outskirts on Jan. 22
by leftist Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, or FARC, guerrillas. The
rebels had demanded $1 million for his release.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Cloning Pioneers End Pig Research
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- The creators of Dolly the Sheep are halting their research
into genetically modifying pigs for human organ transplants, one of the
scientists said today. The decision is motivated in part by fears that
transplanting animal organs into people could unleash deadly new viruses among
the human population. California-based Geron Bio-Med, which owns exclusive
rights to biotechnology developed by Edinburgh's Roslin Institute -- where Dolly
was created -- has decided to cut funding for the work, said Ian Wilmut, leader
of the team that created Dolly, the first clone made from an adult animal.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Ervin Swims Into US Olympic History
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Anthony Ervin made history tonight as the first swimmer
of black heritage to earn a spot on the U.S. Olympic team. Ervin, of Valencia,
Calif., will swim on the 400-meter freestyle relay team at the Sydney Games
after finishing fifth in the 100 free. Most of the attention concerning the
first black to make the team has focused on Sabir Muhammad of Atlanta. He was
also in the 100 free final but finished last in the eight-man field. Both men
plan to swim the 50 free preliminaries Monday.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Red Sox Beat Rangers 4-2
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas (AP) -- Nomar Garciaparra and Jason Varitek hit two-run
singles in the third inning and the Boston Red Sox beat the Texas Rangers 4-2
tonight. Gabe Kapler extended the major leagues' longest hitting streak this
season to 26 games with a sixth-inning single, but Texas had just five hits. The
Rangers have been held to seven hits or less in four straight games.
</P>
