<HEADLINE> Reds 3, Cubs 0  </HEADLINE>
By NANCY ARMOUR
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Sean Casey drove in one run with his bat and
another with his body, and Steve Parris got his first win since
July 8 as the Cincinnati Reds beat the listless Chicago Cubs 3-0
Sunday night for a three-game sweep.
</P>
<P>
   Casey homered and went 3-for-3. Pokey Reese drove in the other
run.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds have now won four in a row and nine of their last 12 on
the road.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time the Cubs had been swept since Florida did
it June 23-25. It also was their first three-game losing streak
since the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   Parris (6-14), who had lost his last three decisions, pitched 7
2-3 scoreless innings, but the Cubs didn't give him much of a
challenge. After Sammy Sosa's three-run homer in the fifth inning
Friday, the Cubs went 22 innings without scoring.
</P>
<P>
   They loaded the bases in the eighth after Parris gave up a
single to Eric Young and walks to Sosa and Ricky Gutierrez, but
reliever Scott Sullivan struck out Rondell White swinging to end
the threat.
</P>
<P>
   Since Sosa's homer, the Cubs are 0-for-20 with runners in
scoring position and 2-for-34 with runners on base. They stranded
nine Sunday, adding to the 13 they left on base Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Parris scattered six hits, struck out three and walked four.
Sullivan got four outs for his third save.
</P>
<P>
   Ruben Quevedo (1-4) gave up three runs and five hits in seven
innings. He also hit two batters -- forcing in a run when he plunked
Casey -- walked three and struck out five.
</P>
<P>
   With the Cubs struggling at the plate, the Reds needed only a
couple of runs and they got them early. Reese hit an RBI double in
the second inning, scoring Dante Bichette.
</P>
<P>
   Casey made it 2-0 with a solo homer in the fourth, his first
since July 25.
</P>
<P>
   In the fifth, Quevedo loaded the bases when he gave up a double
to Barry Larkin, hit Ken Griffey Jr. and walked Bichette. He then
hit Casey to force in a run, giving the Reds a 3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Before the game, Parris ran out to center field, touched
the 400-foot sign and waved to fans. Parris grew up in nearby
Joliet, Ill. ... Former Cub Ryne Sandberg sang ''Take Me Out to the
Ball Game'' in the seventh-inning stretch. ... The Reds' sweep was
their first at Wrigley Field since September 1998. ... The 22
scoreless innings by Reds pitchers marks their longest string of
the season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
