<DOCNO> APW20000813.0139 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 23:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sanders Says He's Done With Football  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND BLANC, Mich. (AP) -- Barry Sanders is finished playing
football and is enjoying life as a former running back for the
Detroit Lions.
</P>
<P>
   ''If I wanted to play football again, all I'd have to do is just
show up (at training camp) in Saginaw or at the Silverdome, Sanders
told the Detroit Free Press on Saturday at the Buick Open.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders retired in July 1999, two days before the start of the
Lions' training camp. He played 10 seasons with the Lions and
gained 15,269 rushing yards, second in NFL history to the late
Walter Payton's 16,726.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders said breaking rushing records or finishing with the most
touchdowns wasn't important to him.
</P>
<P>
   ''So if that's never been important to me, then why would that
be a motivation to keep playing?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders denied his father's comments that he decided to retire
out of dislike for coach Bobby Ross and a poor opinion of the
Lions' front-office.
</P>
<P>
   ''Why would anyone automatically assume that other people were
speaking for me?'' Sanders said.
</P>
<P>
   ''My decision has nothing to do with the Lions,'' he said in a
report published on the Free Press' Web site and in its Monday
editions. ''I know that you probably don't believe me, but it has
nothing to do with the Lions. I played 10 years. And that was
enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Ross told the newspaper on Sunday that Sanders' comments only
confirmed his belief.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have honestly felt that way all along,'' Ross said. ''that
was from my own gut feeling, No. 1, and secondly, he had talked to
other people in this organization and had conveyed that very same
point a number of times.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanders said he was disturbed by the public reaction over his
decision to retire. He was booed when introduced at a fight at Joe
Louis Arena last year.
</P>
<P>
   ''Can't a man just leave his job when he's tired?'' Sanders
said. ''It doesn't have to mean anything more than just a person
who believes that his career is complete.''
</P>
<P>
   In July, Sanders sent the Lions a check for $1.833 million, a
payment he was obligated to make if he doesn't play this season.
The money represents part of a signing bonus Sanders received in
1997, when he signed a six-year contract.
</P>
<P>
   In a February decision, arbitrator Sam Kagel said Sanders owes
the Lions $1.833 million of unearned signing bonus for each year he
doesn't play during the remaining three years of his contract.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-13-00 2306 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
