<HEADLINE> Old Friends To Offer Gore Tributes  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- When Al Gore accepts his party's presidential
nomination, the script for the night will read like an old episode
of ''This Is Your Life.''
</P>
<P>
   A college roommate. An Army buddy. The mountain climber who
guided his ascent of Mount Rainier. They'll all be on hand Thursday
to tell America about their friend, the would-be president.
</P>
<P>
   A ''conversation'' about Gore is how his campaign characterizes
the night.
</P>
<P>
   An Episcopal bishop and longtime family friend, the Rt. Rev.
Jane Holmes Dixon of Washington, D.C., will run the show,
introducing each speaker.
</P>
<P>
   Dixon has known Gore since he was a boy. Dixon introduced Gore's
sister, Nancy, to the man she would marry, Frank Hunger. Nancy Gore
died in 1984 of lung cancer, but Hunger has remained one of Gore's
closest friends, and will talk about Gore's family ties.
</P>
<P>
   Scattered among various politicos on the speaker's list will be:
</P>
<P>
   --John Tyson, Gore's roommate at Harvard University. He now works
for a Washington lobbying firm.
</P>
<P>
   --An Army buddy from the Vietnam War, Robert E. Delabar of
Seattle, who met Gore when both were stationed at Fort Rucker, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   --Jim Frush, a mountain climber who guided Gore's ascent of Mount
Rainier.
</P>
</TEXT>
