<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 23:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ervin Swims Into US Olympic History  </HEADLINE>
By BETH HARRIS
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Anthony Ervin is poised to make history as
the first swimmer of black heritage to earn a spot on the U.S.
Olympic team.
</P>
<P>
   Ervin, of Valencia, Calif., will likely swim on the 400-meter
freestyle relay team at the Sydney Games after finishing fifth in
the 100 free Sunday night. The top four automatically make the
Olympic squad, and there's usually room for the next two as well.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've always been proud of my heritage,'' he said. ''I don't
think of my swimming in terms of race. I've always considered
myself color blind, so I don't even notice it that much.''
</P>
<P>
   Ervin's father, Jack, is 75 percent black and 25 percent
American Indian. His mother, Sherry, is white. The light-skinned
Ervin said in describing himself, ''I don't look black.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the attention concerning the first black to make the
team has focused on Sabir Muhammad of Atlanta. He was also in the
100 free final but finished last in the eight-man field.
</P>
<P>
   Both men plan to swim the 50 free preliminaries Monday. That's
Muhammad best event.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a disappointing race,'' said Muhammad, who finished
more than two seconds behind winner Neil Walker. ''But all my
marbles weren't in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ervin, 19, won the 50 free for California at this year's NCAA
meet with a short-course world record of 21.21 seconds. He also won
the 100 free.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm pretty new to the national scene,'' he said. ''I wasn't a
contender until this year.''
</P>
<P>
   At Cal, Ervin said he ''checks off a bunch'' of boxes on forms
asking for his racial background.
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad owns the American short-course record in the 50
butterfly. His international experience includes the 1995 Pan
Pacific championships and the 1999 Pan American Games. He didn't
medal in either meet.
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad swam at Stanford, where Tiger Woods advised him on
handling the media and attention surrounding his swimming. His
father, Sabir Muhammad Sr., is a reporter covering the trials for
the Muslim Journal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
