<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 23:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Paraguay VP Vote Too Close To Call  </HEADLINE>
By KEVIN GRAY
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) -- Paraguay's vote for a successor to its
slain vice president appeared extremely close Sunday, with early
returns giving the opposition candidate a slim lead over the late
politician's son.
</P>
<P>
   The special, one-office election is seen by the opposition as a
chance to diminish the power of the Colorado Party, which has ruled
this South American country for 53 years. The post of vice
president has been empty since Luis Argana was gunned down in the
street in March 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The winner will enter a unique and possibly unstable governing
situation: an elected vice president alongside a beleaguered
President Luis Gonzalez Macchi, whose popularity has plummeted
since he was thrust into his post -- without benefit of elections --
amid the chaos following Argana's slaying.
</P>
<P>
   With ballots counted from around 90 percent of the polling
stations, the Paraguayan electoral board Sunday evening said
opposition candidate Julio Cesar Franco had 47.77 percent of the
vote. The ruling party's candidate Felix Argana, the son of the
slain vice president, had 46.93 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Election officials reported no incidents of violence during the
voting on a chilly and cloudy winter day. Some 2 million
Paraguayans were eligible to vote. The electoral board said final
results are to be announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking from a balcony at Liberal Party headquarters, the
48-year-old Franco told some 5,000 supporters they were on the
verge of victory.
</P>
<P>
   ''The people have spoken in free, democratic, and transparent
elections,'' he bellowed into a microphone, his neck wrapped in the
party's royal blue flag. ''I want to ask you all to vigilant as
they count the final votes.''
</P>
<P>
   Franco, a doctor, has suggested that if elected he would work to
have Macchi removed from office. A faction of the Colorado Party
has been strongly critical of Macchi, and Franco could look for
their support in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Faces were long at Colorado party headquarters. Argana, 43, had
earlier declared victory, citing his own party's exit polls. But in
the evening, he offered no comment. The Colorado party has ruled
Paraguay since 1947.
</P>
<P>
   It is the first time in Paraguay's history that a vice president
is chosen outside of a presidential election. Macchi has refused to
hold an election to validate his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Macchi, the former Senate president, took office after Raul
Cubas resigned as president in the wake of Argana's death. Cubas
was suspected of being involved in Argana's killing.
</P>
<P>
   Macchi's popularity has dipped to less than 20 percent as
Paraguay struggles through a grinding recession.
</P>
<P>
   Pre-election polls predicted a tight race between Franco, of the
opposition Liberal party, and Argana. The third candidate, Ricardo
Buman of the Humanist Party, was considered a long shot. No run-off
is required if the winner falls short of a 50-percent victory.
</P>
<P>
   Argana, an architect and Asuncion city councilman, voted Sunday
morning after visiting his father's tomb. He has said he does not
intend to overshadow Macchi but to be a stabilizing force in his
troubled administration.
</P>
<P>
   Argana supporters have suggested his election to office would be
a first step toward justice for his father's death. Argana's murder
remains unsolved, although a Paraguayan judge has accused Lino
Oviedo, an army chief and former political ally of Cubas, of
masterminding the killing.
</P>
<P>
   After casting his vote in downtown Asuncion, Franco
enthusiastically flashed his ink-stained forefinger to supporters.
Voters are required to dip their fingers in ink after voting in
order to prevent fraud.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
